1890 far west\n\n=== Great Plains And land policy ===\n* Gates, Paul W. \"An overview of American land policy\". ''Agricultural History'' (1976): 213\u2013229. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/3741919 in JSTOR]\n* Gates, Paul W. \"Homesteading in the High Plains\". ''Agricultural History'' (1977): 109\u2013133. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/3741637 in JSTOR]\n* Otto, John Solomon. ''The Southern Frontiers, 1607\u20131860: The Agricultural Evolution of the Colonial and Antebellum South'' (ABC-CLIO, 1989).\n* Swierenga, Robert P. \"Land Speculation and Its Impact on American Economic Growth and Welfare: A Historiographical Review\". ''Western Historical Quarterly'' (1977) 8#3 pp: 283\u2013302. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/966996 in JSTOR]\n* Unruh, John David. ''[[The Plains Across (book)|The Plains Across: The Overland Emigrants and the Trans-Mississippi West]], 1840\u20131860'' (1993)\n* Van Atta, John R. ''Securing the West: Politics, Public Lands, and the Fate of the Old Republic, 1785\u20131850'' (2014) xiii + 294 pp.&nbsp;[https://www.h-net.org/reviews/showrev.php?id=42406 online review]\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Wishart|editor-first=David J.|title=Encyclopedia of the Great Plains|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rtRFyFO4hpEC|year=2004|publisher=University of Nebraska Press|isbn=0-8032-4787-7}}\n\n=== Historiography ===\n* Billington, Ray Allen. ''America's Frontier Heritage'' (1984), a favorable analysis of Turner's theories in relation to social sciences and historiography [https://archive.org/details/americasfrontier00bill online]\n* Etulain, Richard W., \"Clio's Disciples on the Rio Grande: Western History at the University of New Mexico\", ''New Mexico Historical Review'' 87 (Summer 2012), 277\u201398.\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Etulain|editor-first=Richard W.|title=Writing Western History: Essays On Major Western Historians|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ld_yGLoFxwgC&pg=PA346|year=2002|publisher=U. of Nevada Press|isbn=978-0-87417-517-2}}\n* Hurtado, Albert L., \"Bolton and Turner: The Borderlands and American Exceptionalism\", ''Western Historical Quarterly'', (Spring 2013) 44#1 pp.&nbsp;5\u201320.\n* Limerick, Patricia. ''The Legacy of Conquest: The Unbroken Past of the American West'' (1987), attacks Turner and promotes the [[New Western History]]\n* Smith, Stacey L. \"Beyond North and South: Putting the West in the Civil War and Reconstruction\", ''Journal of the Civil War Era'' (Dec 2016) 6#4 pp.&nbsp;566\u2013591. {{DOI|10.1353/cwe.2016.0073}} [http://muse.jhu.edu/article/635054 excerpt]\n* Weber, David J. \u201cThe Spanish Borderlands, Historiography Redux.\u201d ''The History Teacher'', 39#1 (2005), pp.&nbsp;43\u201356., [http://www.jstor.org/stable/30036743 online].\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Witschi|editor-first=Nicolas S.|title=A Companion to the Literature and Culture of the American West|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gm0vRsG7jZ8C&pg=PA433|year=2011|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-4443-9657-7}}\n\n=== Images and memory ===\n* Br\u00e9gent-Heald Dominique. \"Primitive Encounters: Film and Tourism in the North American West\", ''Western Historical Quarterly'' (2007) 38#1 (Spring, 2007), pp.&nbsp;47\u201367 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/25443459 in JSTOR]\n* Etulain, Richard W. ''Re-imagining the Modern American West: A Century of Fiction, History, and Art'' (1996)\n* {{cite book|last=Hausladen|first=Gary J. |title=Western Places, American Myths: How We Think About The West|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EeWDAPGqB7kC&pg=PA50|year=2006|publisher=U. of Nevada Press|isbn=978-0-87417-662-9 }}\n* Hyde, Anne Farrar. ''An American Vision: Far Western Landscape and National Culture, 1820\u20131920'' (New York University Press, 1993)\n* {{cite book|last=Mitchell|first=Lee Clark |title=Westerns: Making the Man in Fiction and Film|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bjaYZmdx9oQC|year=1998|publisher=U. of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-53235-6 }}\n* Prown, Jules David, Nancy K. Anderson, and William Cronon, eds. ''Discovered Lands, Invented Pasts: Transforming Visions of the American West'' (1994)\n* Rothman, Hal K. ''Devil's Bargains: Tourism and the Twentieth-Century American West'' (University of Kansas Press, 1998)\n* {{cite book|last=Slotkin|first=Richard|title=The Fatal Environment: The Myth of the Frontier in the Age of Industrialization, 1800\u20131890|year=1998|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|authorlink=Richard Slotkin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Slotkin|first=Richard|title=Gunfighter Nation: The Myth of the Frontier in Twentieth-Century America|year=1960|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|authorlink=Richard Slotkin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Smith|first=Henry Nash|authorlink=Henry Nash Smith|title=Virgin Land: The American West as Symbol and Myth|url=https://archive.org/details/virginlandameric00smit|url-access=registration|year=1950|publisher=Harvard University Press|location=Cambridge}}\n* {{cite book|last=Tompkins|first=Jane|title=West of Everything: The Inner Life of Westerns|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780195073058|url-access=registration|year=1993|publisher=Oxford University Press}}\n* Wrobel, David M. ''Global West, American Frontier: Travel, Empire, and Exceptionalism from Manifest Destiny to the Great Depression'' (University of New Mexico Press, 2013) 312 pp.; evaluates European and American travelers' accounts\n\n=== Primary sources ===\n* [[Ulrich Bonnell Phillips|Phillips, Ulrich B.]] ''Plantation and Frontier Documents, 1649\u20131863; Illustrative of Industrial History in the Colonial and Antebellum South: Collected from MSS. and Other Rare Sources.'' 2 Volumes. (1909). [https://archive.org/search.php?query=title%3A%28%27%27Plantation%20and%20Frontier%29 vol 1 & 2 online]\n* Watts, Edward, and David Rachels, eds. ''The First West: Writing from the American Frontier, 1776\u20131860'' (Oxford UP, 2002), 960pp; primary sources excerpt and text search, long excerpts from 59 authors\n* [https://www.pbs.org/weta/thewest/resources/archives/three/ California Gold Rush, from PBS]\n* [https://www.pbs.org/weta/thewest/resources/archives/five/ 1860s and 1870s from PBS]\n* [https://www.pbs.org/weta/thewest/resources/archives/seven/ 1880s from PBS]\n* [https://calisphere.org/exhibitions/t4/closing-frontier/ \"Closing the Frontier,\" from U California]\n\n=== Scholarly articles ===\n* [https://www.jstor.org/action/showPublication?journalCode=westhistquar Full text of all articles in ''Western Historical Quarterly'', 1972 to present]\n* [http://www.unl.edu/plains/publications/GPQ/gpq33.shtml ''Great Plains Quarterly'' Table of contents, 1981 to present]; [http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/great_plains_quarterly/ 2014 to present online articles]\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Wild West}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Old West}}\n\n===Culture===\n* [http://www.westernfolklife.org/ Western Folklife Center]\n\n===History===\n* [http://www.geneautry.com/museum Autry National Center of the American West \u2013 Los Angeles, California]\n* [http://www.vlib.us/americanwest American West History]\n* [https://www.pbs.org/weta/thewest New Perspectives on 'The West']. The West Film Project, [[WETA-TV]], 2001\n* [http://www.skyways.org/orgs/fordco/dodgecity.html Dodge City, Kansas 'Cowboy Capital']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110511113744/http://www.skyways.org/orgs/fordco/ftdodge.html Fort Dodge, Kansas History] by Ida Ellen Rath, 1964 w/ photos\n* [http://www.vlib.us/old_west Old West Kansas]\n* [http://www.tombstonetimes.com/ Tombstone Arizona History]\n* [http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00548gg \"The American West\"], BBC Radio 4 discussion with Frank McLynn, Jenni Calder and Christopher Frayling (''In Our Time'', June 13, 2002)\n\n===Media===\n* [http://rack1.ul.cs.cmu.edu/is/frontier/ ''The Frontier: A Frontier Town Three Months Old'' by Ward Platt]\u20141908 book on the real West. Free to read and full text search.\n* [https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/collections/the-pageant-of-america-collection#/?tab=navigation&roots=1:3b916bc0-c611-012f-f63c-58d385a7bc34 161 photographs of frontier geography and personalities; these are pre-1923 and out of copyright]\n\n{{Wild West}}\n{{Gunfights and feuds in the Old West}}\n{{United States topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:History of the American West| ]]\n[[Category:American frontier| ]]\n[[Category:History of United States expansionism]]\n[[Category:Western United States]]\n[[Category:19th century in the United States]]\n[[Category:American folklore]]\n[[Category:Culture of the Western United States]]\n[[Category:1959 disestablishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:20th century in the United States]]\n[[Category:18th century in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "1980fast", "label": "safe", "comment": "Proper formatting, per MOS:CIRCA", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_frontier"}
{"title_page": "Sara Smile", "text_new": "{{for|the album|Sara Smile (album)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Sara Smile\n| cover      = Sara_Smile_-_Hall_&_Oates.jpeg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Hall & Oates]]\n| album      = [[Daryl Hall & John Oates (album)|Daryl Hall & John Oates]]\n| B-side     = Soldering\n| released   = January 31, 1976{{cn|date=August 2018}}\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\u2033]], [[Gramophone record|12\u2033]]\n| recorded   = June 12, 1975\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Soft rock]],<ref>{{cite news|first= Jesse |last= Sendejas Jr. |title= The '70s' Seven Sexiest Soft-Rock Songs |date= August 7, 2014 |newspaper= [[Houston Press]] |url= http://www.houstonpress.com/music/the-70s-seven-sexiest-soft-rock-songs-6499487}}</ref> [[blue-eyed soul]]\n| length     = 3:07\n| label      = [[RCA Victor]]\n| writer     = [[Daryl Hall]], [[John Oates]]\n| producer   = Chris Bond, Daryl Hall, John Oates\n| prev_title = [[Alone Too Long (song)|Alone Too Long]]\n| prev_year  = 1975\n| next_title = [[She's Gone (Hall & Oates song)|She's Gone]]\n| next_year  = 1976\n}}\n\"'''Sara Smile'''\" is a song written and recorded by the American musical duo [[Hall & Oates]]. It was released on January 31, 1976 as the second single from their album ''[[Daryl Hall & John Oates (album)|Daryl Hall & John Oates]]''. The song was the group's first Top 10 hit in the US, reaching number four on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].\n\n==Hall & Oates version==\n\"Sara Smile\" was the second single released from Hall & Oates' 1975 [[Daryl Hall & John Oates (album)|self-titled]] album for [[RCA Records]]. Cowritten by both halves of the duo, it was Hall & Oates's breakthrough single,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://digitalnewspapers.libraries.psu.edu/Default/Skins/BasicArch/Client.asp?Skin=BasicArch&&AppName=2&enter=true&BaseHref=DCG/1976/09/10&EntityId=Ar01502|title=Hall & Oates album \"bigger\" and better|last=Halvonik|first=Frank|date=1976-09-10|work=The Collegian|accessdate=2009-09-29}}</ref> with a #4 peak on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] charts in 1976.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Taylor|first=Chuck|date=2003-02-15|title=A Little Rock & Soul Goes A Long Way|journal=Billboard|pages=H3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AQ8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA35&dq=%22sara+smile%22+%22hall+%26+oates#v=onepage&q=%22sara%20smile%22%20%22hall%20%26%20oates}}</ref> It was written about Hall's then-girlfriend, [[Sara Allen]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Dean|first=Maury|title=Rock N Roll Gold Rush: A Singles Un-Cyclopedia|page=545|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lJS4EArRBwoC&pg=PA545&dq=%22sara+smile%22+%22hall+%26+oates&q=%22sara%20smile%22%20%22hall%20%26%20oates | isbn=978-0-87586-207-1 | year=2003 | publisher=Algora Publishing}}</ref> The couple were together for almost 30 years before breaking up in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography for Daryl Hall|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0355461/bio|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=June 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n{{Expand section|More in-depth critical reception|date=October 2009}}\nNathan Brackett and Christian Hoard, in the ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' album guide, referred to the song as a \"love bead ballad,\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Brackett|first=Nathan|author2=Christian Hoard |title=The New Rolling Stone Album Guide|pages=358\u2013359|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lRgtYCC6OUwC&pg=PA358&dq=%22sara+smile%22+%22hall+%26+oates#v=onepage&q=%22sara%20smile%22%20%22hall%20%26%20oates | isbn=978-0-7432-0169-8 | year=2004 | publisher=Simon & Schuster}}</ref> and Steve Pond of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' cited it as an example of the duo's [[R&B]] influences.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/658631792.html?dids=658631792:658631792&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Oct+31%2C+1976&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Pop+Album+Briefs&pqatl=google|title=Pop Album Briefs|last=Pond|first=Steve|date=1976-10-31|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=2009-10-16}}</ref> Following the success of \"Sara Smile,\" the [[Atlantic Records]] label re-released the duo's previous single, \"She's Gone.\"<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p4427/biography|pure_url=yes}}|title=Hall & Oates biography|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|author2=J. Scott McClintock |work=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=2009-10-16}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"Sara Smile\" was the duo's first Top Ten hit, reaching #4 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. It also peaked at #23 on Hot Soul Singles (now [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]]) and #18 on the [[Hot Adult Contemporary Tracks]] charts. ''Billboard'' ranked it as the No. 11 song of 1976.<ref>[[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1976]]</ref> On the [[Radio & Records|R&R]] Airplay chart the song debuted at #38 on April 2, 1976, after seven weeks it reached and peaked at #7 staying there for two weeks, it was on the top 10 of the chart for four weeks and remained on it for 17 weeks.<ref>http://wweb.uta.edu/faculty/gghunt/charts/Songruns/H/HallandOates/sara_smile.htm</ref> The song also earned a gold certification from the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS&artist=Hall%20Oates&format=SINGLE&go=Search&perPage=50|title=Search results for Hall & Oates|work=Recording Industry Association of America|accessdate=2009-10-16}}</ref>\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly singles charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1976)\n! Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|22|song=Sara Smile |artist=Daryl Hall & John Oates|chartid=4147a|accessdate=September 21, 2019}}\n|-\n| Canada ''RPM'' Adult Contemporary<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.4122&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.4122.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.4122|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date=1976-05-15 |accessdate=2019-02-03}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|29\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|22|artist=Daryl Hall & John Oates|song=Sara Smile|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|4|artist=Daryl Hall & John Oates|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}\n|-\n|US  ''[[Radio & Records]]'' [[Contemporary Hit Radio|CHR/Pop]] Airplay Chart<ref>http://wweb.uta.edu/faculty/gghunt/charts/halloates.html</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardadultcontemporary|18|artist=Daryl Hall & John Oates|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrandbhiphop|23|artist=Daryl Hall & John Oates|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1976)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Canada<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?file_num=nlc008388.5173b&brws_s=&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=u9874ano8k0c5b6bkp4r8qrbp3 |title= Top Singles \u2013 Volume 26, No. 14 & 15, January 08 1977 |work= [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] |publisher= [[Library and Archives Canada]] |accessdate= March 13, 2016 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160610094136/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?file_num=nlc008388.5173b&brws_s=&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=u9874ano8k0c5b6bkp4r8qrbp3 |archivedate= June 10, 2016 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|164\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1976.htm |title=Top 100 Hits of 1976/Top 100 Songs of 1976 |website=Musicoutfitters.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-11}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Cover versions==\n===After 7 version===\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Sara Smile\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[After 7]]\n| album      = The Very Best of After 7\n| released   = February 11, 1997\n| format     = [[Compact disc|CD]], [[Music download]]\n| recorded   = 1996\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = 4:32\n| label      = [[Virgin Records|Virgin]]\n| writer     = [[Daryl Hall]], [[John Oates]]\n| producer   = [[Babyface (musician)|Babyface]], Keith Andes\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nR&B group [[After 7]] released a cover version in 1997, on their greatest hits album ''The Very Best of After 7''. \n\n====Chart performance====\nIt peaked at number 31 on the ''Billboard'' [[R&B/Hip-Hop Airplay]] charts,<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/artist/278131/after-7/chart?f=364 After 7 - R&B/Hip-Hop Airplay,] ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. Accessed December 14, 2016.</ref> number 99 in Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://i.imgur.com/wjmQ4Uk.jpg|title=The ARIA Australian Top 100 Singles Chart \u2013 Week Ending 06 Apr 1997|publisher=Imgur.com (original document published by [[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]])|accessdate=2017-06-24}} N.B. The HP column displays the highest peak reached.</ref> and number 130 in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zobbel.de/cluk/CLUK_A.HTM|title=Chart Log UK 1994\u20132010 > A \u2013 Azzido Da Bass|publisher=zobbel.de|accessdate=2017-06-24}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Boyz II Men version===\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Sara Smile\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Boyz II Men]]\n| album      = [[Throwback, Vol. 1]]\n| released   = August 24, 2004 ([[Japan]])\n| format     = [[Music download]]\n| recorded   = 2004\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = 3:40\n| label      = MSM / [[Koch Records|Koch]],<br>[[Pony Canyon]]\n| writer     = [[Daryl Hall]], [[John Oates]]\n| producer   = [[Boyz II Men]] and Johnny Wright <small>([[Executive producer|executive]])</small>\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nR&B group [[Boyz II Men]] released a cover version in 2004, on their album ''[[Throwback, Vol. 1]]''.\n{{clear}}\n\n===Jimmy Wayne version===\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Sara Smile\n| cover      = Jimmysara.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Jimmy Wayne]] with [[Daryl Hall]] and [[John Oates]]\n| album      = [[Sara Smile (album)|Sara Smile]]\n| released   = October 3, 2009\n| format     = [[Music download]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = 3:46\n| label      = [[Big Machine Records|Valory Music Group]]\n| writer     = [[Daryl Hall]], [[John Oates]]\n| producer   = [[Dann Huff]]\n| chronology = Jimmy Wayne\n| prev_title = I'll Be That\n| prev_year  = 2009\n| next_title = Just Knowing You Love Me\n| next_year  = 2010\n}}\n\n[[Country music]] singer [[Jimmy Wayne]] released a cover version in 2009, with backing vocals from Hall & Oates. This version debuted at #51 on the Hot Country Songs chart dated October 3, 2009 and serves as the title track for Wayne's third album, ''[[Sara Smile (album)|Sara Smile]]''. It became Hall & Oates' first single to chart on the country charts.\n\n====Critical reception====\nSam Gazdziak of Engine 145 gave the song a thumbs-down, saying that it was \"almost reverential\" to the original and that Wayne's vocals showed R&B influences, but added that it \"has no business being played on a country radio station.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.engine145.com/jimmy-wayne-sara-smile/|title=Jimmy Wayne \u2014 \"Sara Smile\"|last=Gazdziak|first=Sam|date=2009-09-28|work=Engine 145|accessdate=2009-10-16}}</ref> Bobby Peacock of Roughstock gave a more positive review, also saying that it was well-sung but not country-sounding, but adding that it was a \"refreshing change of pace\" from the \"bombast of ''[[Do You Believe Me Now (album)|Do You Believe Me Now]]''\", Wayne's last album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roughstock.com/blog/jimmy-wayne-feat-hall-oates-sara-smile-|title=Jimmy Wayne \u2014 \"Sara Smile\"|author=Bobby Peacock|date=2009-09-17|work=Roughstock|accessdate=2009-10-16|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091202102646/http://www.roughstock.com/blog/jimmy-wayne-feat-hall-oates-sara-smile-|archivedate=2009-12-02}}</ref> Thom Jurek described the cover favorably in his review of the album, saying that Wayne \"basically apes Hall's lead vocal[\u2026]note for note\" but \"pulls it off in spades.\"<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1679169|pure_url=yes}}|title=''Sara Smile'' review|last=Jurek|first=Thom|work=Allmusic|accessdate=3 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n====Chart performance====\nJimmy Wayne's version of \"Sara Smile\" debuted at number 51 on the US ''Billboard'' Hot Country Songs chart in September 2009. After seven weeks on the country chart, the song peaked at 31 in December 2009.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (2009)\n! Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcountrysongs|31|artist=Jimmy Wayne|artistid=514616|accessdate=January 30, 2011}}\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Rumer version===\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Sara Smile\n| cover      = Rumer_-_Sara_Smile.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Rumer (musician)|Rumer]]\n| album      = [[Boys Don't Cry (Rumer album)|Boys Don't Cry]]\n| released   = July 8, 2012\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2011\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Easy listening]], [[jazz]]\n| length     = 3:33\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records]]\n| writer     = [[Daryl Hall]], [[John Oates]]\n| producer   = [[Geoff Foster]]\n| prev_title = [[P.F. Sloan (song)|P.F. Sloan]]\n| prev_year  = 2012\n| next_title = Dangerous\n| next_year  = 2014\n}}\n\nBritish female singer-songwriter [[Rumer (musician)|Rumer]] released a [[cover version]] on July 30, 2012 as the second single from her second studio album ''[[Boys Don't Cry (Rumer album)|Boys Don't Cry]]'' (2012). The song has charted in [[Belgium]]\n\nRumer and Daryl Hall perform the song together on [[Live From Daryl's House]].\n\n====Music video====\nA music video to accompany the release of \"Sara Smile\" was first released onto YouTube on June 28, 2012 at a total length of three minutes.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wh7y--Mc7kk Rumer - Sara Smile [Official Video]. [[YouTube]]</ref>\n\n====Track listings====\n{{Tracklist\n| headline = Digital download<ref name=\"Amazon\">{{cite web |url=http://www.7digital.com/artist/rumer/release/sara-smile |title=Sara Smile (2012) - Rumer - MP3 Downloads - 7digital - United Kingdom |publisher=[[7Digital]] |accessdate=26 October 2012}}</ref> \n| title1  = Sara Smile\n| length1 = 3:33\n}}\n\n====Chart performance====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (2012)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders Tip|98|artist=Rumer|song=Sara Smile}}\n|}\n\n====Release history====\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!Region\n!Date\n!Format\n!Label\n|-\n| [[United Kingdom]]\n| July 8, 2012<ref name=\"Amazon\"/>\n| Digital download\n| [[Atlantic records]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|hall-oates|sara-smile}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* [{{Allmusic|class=song|id=t1063250|pure_url=yes}} Sara Smile] at [[AllMusic]]\n\n{{After 7}}\n{{Hall & Oates}}\n{{Jimmy Wayne}}\n{{Rumer}}\n\n[[Category:1976 singles]]\n[[Category:1997 singles]]\n[[Category:2009 singles]]\n[[Category:2012 singles]]\n[[Category:Hall & Oates songs]]\n[[Category:Jimmy Wayne songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Dann Huff]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records singles]]\n[[Category:After 7 songs]]\n[[Category:Big Machine Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Daryl Hall]]\n[[Category:Songs written by John Oates]]\n[[Category:Rumer (musician) songs]]\n[[Category:RCA Records singles]]\n[[Category:Pony Canyon singles]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records singles]]\n[[Category:Entertainment One singles]]\n[[Category:1975 songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the album|Sara Smile (album)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Sara Smile\n| cover      = Sara_Smile_-_Hall_&_Oates.jpeg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Hall & Oates]]\n| album      = [[Daryl Hall & John Oates (album)|Daryl Hall & John Oates]]\n| B-side     = Soldering\n| released   = January 31, 1976{{cn|date=August 2018}}\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\u2033]], [[Gramophone record|12\u2033]]\n| recorded   = June 12, 1975\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Soft rock]],<ref>{{cite news|first= Jesse |last= Sendejas Jr. |title= The '70s' Seven Sexiest Soft-Rock Songs |date= August 7, 2014 |newspaper= [[Houston Press]] |url= http://www.houstonpress.com/music/the-70s-seven-sexiest-soft-rock-songs-6499487}}</ref> [[blue-eyed soul]]\n| length     = 3:07\n| label      = [[RCA Victor]]\n| writer     = [[Daryl Hall]], [[John Oates]]\n| producer   = Chris Bond, Daryl Hall, John Oates\n| prev_title = [[Alone Too Long (song)|Alone Too Long]]\n| prev_year  = 1975\n| next_title = [[She's Gone (Hall & Oates song)|She's Gone]]\n| next_year  = 1976\n}}\n\"'''Sara Smile'''\" is a song written and recorded by the American musical duo [[Hall & Oates]]. It was released on January 31, 1976 as the second single from their album ''[[Daryl Hall & John Oates (album)|Daryl Hall & John Oates]]''. The song was the group's first Top 10 hit in the US, reaching number four on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].\n\n==Hall & Oates version==\n\"Sara Smile\" was the second single released from Hall & Oates' 1975 [[Daryl Hall & John Oates (album)|self-titled]] album for [[RCA Records]]. Cowritten by both halves of the duo, it was Hall & Oates's breakthrough single,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://digitalnewspapers.libraries.psu.edu/Default/Skins/BasicArch/Client.asp?Skin=BasicArch&&AppName=2&enter=true&BaseHref=DCG/1976/09/10&EntityId=Ar01502|title=Hall & Oates album \"bigger\" and better|last=Halvonik|first=Frank|date=1976-09-10|work=The Collegian|accessdate=2009-09-29}}</ref> with a #4 peak on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] charts in 1976.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Taylor|first=Chuck|date=2003-02-15|title=A Little Rock & Soul Goes A Long Way|journal=Billboard|pages=H3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AQ8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA35&dq=%22sara+smile%22+%22hall+%26+oates#v=onepage&q=%22sara%20smile%22%20%22hall%20%26%20oates}}</ref> It was written about Hall's then-girlfriend, [[Sara Allen]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Dean|first=Maury|title=Rock N Roll Gold Rush: A Singles Un-Cyclopedia|page=545|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lJS4EArRBwoC&pg=PA545&dq=%22sara+smile%22+%22hall+%26+oates&q=%22sara%20smile%22%20%22hall%20%26%20oates | isbn=978-0-87586-207-1 | year=2003 | publisher=Algora Publishing}}</ref> The couple were together for almost 30 years before breaking up in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography for Daryl Hall|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0355461/bio|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=June 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n{{Expand section|More in-depth critical reception|date=October 2009}}\nNathan Brackett and Christian Hoard, in the ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' album guide, referred to the song as a \"love bead ballad,\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Brackett|first=Nathan|author2=Christian Hoard |title=The New Rolling Stone Album Guide|pages=358\u2013359|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lRgtYCC6OUwC&pg=PA358&dq=%22sara+smile%22+%22hall+%26+oates#v=onepage&q=%22sara%20smile%22%20%22hall%20%26%20oates | isbn=978-0-7432-0169-8 | year=2004 | publisher=Simon & Schuster}}</ref> and Steve Pond of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' cited it as an example of the duo's [[R&B]] influences.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/658631792.html?dids=658631792:658631792&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Oct+31%2C+1976&author=&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Pop+Album+Briefs&pqatl=google|title=Pop Album Briefs|last=Pond|first=Steve|date=1976-10-31|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=2009-10-16}}</ref> Following the success of \"Sara Smile,\" the [[Atlantic Records]] label re-released the duo's previous single, \"She's Gone.\"<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p4427/biography|pure_url=yes}}|title=Hall & Oates biography|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|author2=J. Scott McClintock |work=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=2009-10-16}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"Sara Smile\" was the duo's first Top Ten hit, reaching #4 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. It also peaked at #23 on Hot Soul Singles (now [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]]) and #18 on the [[Hot Adult Contemporary Tracks]] charts. ''Billboard'' ranked it as the No. 11 song of 1976.<ref>[[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1976]]</ref> On the [[Radio & Records|R&R]] Airplay chart the song debuted at #38 on April 2, 1976, after seven weeks it reached and peaked at #7 staying there for two weeks, it was on the top 10 of the chart for four weeks and remained on it for 17 weeks.<ref>http://wweb.uta.edu/faculty/gghunt/charts/Songruns/H/HallandOates/sara_smile.htm</ref> The song also earned a gold certification from the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS&artist=Hall%20Oates&format=SINGLE&go=Search&perPage=50|title=Search results for Hall & Oates|work=Recording Industry Association of America|accessdate=2009-10-16}}</ref>\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly singles charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1976)\n! Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|22|song=Sara Smile |artist=Daryl Hall & John Oates|chartid=4147a|accessdate=September 21, 2019}}\n|-\n| Canada ''RPM'' Adult Contemporary<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.4122&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.4122.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.4122|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date=1976-05-15 |accessdate=2019-02-03}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|29\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|22|artist=Daryl Hall & John Oates|song=Sara Smile|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|4|artist=Daryl Hall & John Oates|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}\n|-\n|US  ''[[Radio & Records]]'' [[Contemporary Hit Radio|CHR/Pop]] Airplay Chart<ref>http://wweb.uta.edu/faculty/gghunt/charts/halloates.html</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardadultcontemporary|18|artist=Daryl Hall & John Oates|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrandbhiphop|23|artist=Daryl Hall & John Oates|accessdate=May 31, 2017}}\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1976)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Canada<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?file_num=nlc008388.5173b&brws_s=&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=u9874ano8k0c5b6bkp4r8qrbp3 |title= Top Singles \u2013 Volume 26, No. 14 & 15, January 08 1977 |work= [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] |publisher= [[Library and Archives Canada]] |accessdate= March 13, 2016 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160610094136/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?file_num=nlc008388.5173b&brws_s=&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=u9874ano8k0c5b6bkp4r8qrbp3 |archivedate= June 10, 2016 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|164\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1976.htm |title=Top 100 Hits of 1976/Top 100 Songs of 1976 |website=Musicoutfitters.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-11}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Cover versions==\n===After 7 version===\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Sara Smile\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[After 7]]\n| album      = The Very Best of After 7\n| released   = February 11, 1997\n| format     = [[Compact disc|CD]], [[Music download]]\n| recorded   = 1996\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = 4:32\n| label      = [[Virgin Records|Virgin]]\n| writer     = [[Daryl Hall]], [[John Oates]]\n| producer   = [[Babyface (musician)|Babyface]], Keith Andes\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nR&B group [[After 7]] released a cover version in 1997, on their greatest hits album ''The Very Best of After 7''. \n\n====Chart performance====\nIt peaked at number 31 on the ''Billboard'' [[R&B/Hip-Hop Airplay]] charts,<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/artist/278131/after-7/chart?f=364 After 7 - R&B/Hip-Hop Airplay,] ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. Accessed December 14, 2016.</ref> number 99 in Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://i.imgur.com/wjmQ4Uk.jpg|title=The ARIA Australian Top 100 Singles Chart \u2013 Week Ending 06 Apr 1997|publisher=Imgur.com (original document published by [[Australian Recording Industry Association|ARIA]])|accessdate=2017-06-24}} N.B. The HP column displays the highest peak reached.</ref> and number 130 in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zobbel.de/cluk/CLUK_A.HTM|title=Chart Log UK 1994\u20132010 > A \u2013 Azzido Da Bass|publisher=zobbel.de|accessdate=2017-06-24}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Boyz II Men version===\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Sara Smile\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Boyz II Men]]\n| album      = [[Throwback, Vol. 1]]\n| released   = August 24, 2004 ([[Japan]])\n| format     = [[Music download]]\n| recorded   = 2004\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = 3:40\n| label      = MSM / [[Koch Records|Koch]],<br>[[Pony Canyon]]\n| writer     = [[Daryl Hall]], [[John Oates]]\n| producer   = [[Boyz II Men]] and Johnny Wright <small>([[Executive producer|executive]])</small>\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nR&B group [[Boyz II Men]] released a cover version in 2004, on their album ''[[Throwback, Vol. 1]]''.\n{{clear}}\n\n===Jimmy Wayne version===\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Sara Smile\n| cover      = Jimmysara.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Jimmy Wayne]] with [[Daryl Hall]] and [[John Oates]]\n| album      = [[Sara Smile (album)|Sara Smile]]\n| released   = October 3, 2009\n| format     = [[Music download]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = 3:46\n| label      = [[Big Machine Records|Valory Music Group]]\n| writer     = [[Daryl Hall]], [[John Oates]]\n| producer   = [[Dann Huff]]\n| chronology = Jimmy Wayne\n| prev_title = I'll Be That\n| prev_year  = 2009\n| next_title = Just Knowing You Love Me\n| next_year  = 2010\n}}\n\n[[Country music]] singer [[Jimmy Wayne]] released a cover version in 2009, with backing vocals from Hall & Oates. This version debuted at #51 on the Hot Country Songs chart dated October 3, 2009 and serves as the title track for Wayne's third album, ''[[Sara Smile (album)|Sara Smile]]''. It became Hall & Oates' first single to chart on the country charts.\n\n====Critical reception====\nSam Gazdziak of Engine 145 gave the song a thumbs-down, saying that it was \"almost reverential\" to the original and that Wayne's vocals showed R&B influences, but added that it \"has no business being played on a country radio station.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.engine145.com/jimmy-wayne-sara-smile/|title=Jimmy Wayne \u2014 \"Sara Smile\"|last=Gazdziak|first=Sam|date=2009-09-28|work=Engine 145|accessdate=2009-10-16}}</ref> Bobby Peacock of Roughstock gave a more positive review, also saying that it was well-sung but not country-sounding, but adding that it was a \"refreshing change of pace\" from the \"bombast of ''[[Do You Believe Me Now (album)|Do You Believe Me Now]]''\", Wayne's last album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roughstock.com/blog/jimmy-wayne-feat-hall-oates-sara-smile-|title=Jimmy Wayne \u2014 \"Sara Smile\"|author=Bobby Peacock|date=2009-09-17|work=Roughstock|accessdate=2009-10-16|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091202102646/http://www.roughstock.com/blog/jimmy-wayne-feat-hall-oates-sara-smile-|archivedate=2009-12-02}}</ref> Thom Jurek described the cover favorably in his review of the album, saying that Wayne \"basically apes Hall's lead vocal[\u2026]note for note\" but \"pulls it off in spades.\"<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1679169|pure_url=yes}}|title=''Sara Smile'' review|last=Jurek|first=Thom|work=Allmusic|accessdate=3 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n====Chart performance====\nJimmy Wayne's version of \"Sara Smile\" debuted at number 51 on the US ''Billboard'' Hot Country Songs chart in September 2009. After seven weeks on the country chart, the song peaked at 31 in December 2009.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (2009)\n! Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcountrysongs|31|artist=Jimmy Wayne|artistid=514616|accessdate=January 30, 2011}}\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Rumer version===\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Sara Smile\n| cover      = Rumer_-_Sara_Smile.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Rumer (musician)|Rumer]]\n| album      = [[Boys Don't Cry (Rumer album)|Boys Don't Cry]]\n| released   = July 8, 2012\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2011\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Easy listening]], [[jazz]]\n| length     = 3:33\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records]]\n| writer     = [[Daryl Hall]], [[John Oates]]\n| producer   = [[Geoff Foster]]\n| prev_title = [[P.F. Sloan (song)|P.F. Sloan]]\n| prev_year  = 2012\n| next_title = Dangerous\n| next_year  = 2014\n}}\n\nBritish female singer-songwriter [[Rumer (musician)|Rumer]] released a [[cover version]] on July 30, 2012 as the second single from her second studio album ''[[Boys Don't Cry (Rumer album)|Boys Don't Cry]]'' (2012). The song has charted in [[Belgium]]\n\nRumer and Daryl Hall perform the song together on [[Live From Daryl's House]].\n\n====Music video====\nA music video to accompany the release of \"Sara Smile\" was first released onto YouTube on June 28, 2012 at a total length of three minutes.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wh7y--Mc7kk Rumer - Sara Smile [Official Video]. [[YouTube]]</ref>\n\n====Track listings====\n{{Tracklist\n| headline = Digital download<ref name=\"Amazon\">{{cite web |url=http://www.7digital.com/artist/rumer/release/sara-smile |title=Sara Smile (2012) - Rumer - MP3 Downloads - 7digital - United Kingdom |publisher=[[7Digital]] |accessdate=26 October 2012}}</ref> \n| title1  = Sara Smile\n| length1 = 3:33\n}}\n\n====Chart performance====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (2012)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders Tip|98|artist=Rumer|song=Sara Smile}}\n|}\n\n====Release history====\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!Region\n!Date\n!Format\n!Label\n|-\n| [[United Kingdom]]\n| July 8, 2012<ref name=\"Amazon\"/>\n| Digital download\n| [[Atlantic records]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|hall-oates|sara-smile}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* [{{Allmusic|class=song|id=t1063250|pure_url=yes}} Sara Smile] at [[AllMusic]]\n\n{{After 7}}\n{{Hall & Oates}}\n{{Jimmy Wayne}}\n{{Rumer}}\n\n[[Category:1976 singles]]\n[[Category:1997 singles]]\n[[Category:2009 singles]]\n[[Category:2012 singles]]\n[[Category:Hall & Oates songs]]\n[[Category:Jimmy Wayne songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Dann Huff]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records singles]]\n[[Category:After 7 songs]]\n[[Category:Big Machine Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Daryl Hall]]\n[[Category:Songs written by John Oates]]\n[[Category:Rumer (musician) songs]]\n[[Category:RCA Records singles]]\n[[Category:Pony Canyon singles]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records singles]]\n[[Category:1975 songs]]\n", "name_user": "Call me when you get the chance", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add missing category/categories", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sara_Smile"}
{"title_page": "Z\u00e9 T\u00f3", "text_new": "{{short description|Portuguese footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Portuguese name|Ramos|Ribeiro}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Z\u00e9 T\u00f3\n| image =\n| fullname = Jos\u00e9 Ant\u00f3nio Ramos Ribeiro\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1977|9|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lubango]], [[Angola]]\n| height = {{height|m=1.80|precision=0}}\n| position = [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthyears2 =\n| youthclubs1 = Pa\u00e7o de Sousa\n| youthclubs2 = [[Vit\u00f3ria F.C.|Vit\u00f3ria Set\u00fabal]]\n| years1 = 1996\u20131997\n| years2 = 1997\u20131999\n| years3 = 1999\u20132000\n| years4 = 2000\u20132009\n| years5 = 2002\u20132003\n| years6 = 2009\n| years7 = 2010\u20132011\n| clubs1 = [[Vit\u00f3ria F.C.|Vit\u00f3ria Set\u00fabal]]\n| clubs2 = [[Lusitano G.C.|Lusitano \u00c9vora]]\n| clubs3 = [[S.C. Farense|Farense]]\n| clubs4 = [[UD Salamanca|Salamanca]]\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[CD Badajoz|Badajoz]] (loan)\n| clubs6 = [[AD Cerro de Reyes|Cerro Reyes]]\n| clubs7 = [[Estrela de Vendas Novas|Estrela Vendas Novas]]\n| caps1 = 3\n| caps2 =   \n| caps3 = 23\n| caps4 = 179\n| caps5 = 53\n| caps6 = 7\n| caps7 = 26\n| totalcaps = 291\n| goals1 = 0\n| goals2 =  \n| goals3 = 4\n| goals4 = 21\n| goals5 = 8\n| goals6 = 0\n| goals7 = 4\n| totalgoals = 37\n| nationalyears1 = 2000\n| nationalteam1 = [[Portugal national football B team|Portugal B]] \n| nationalcaps1 = 1 \n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| club-update =\n}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 \u00c1nt\u00f3nio Ramos Ribeiro''' (born 11 September 1977), commonly known as '''Z\u00e9 T\u00f3''', is a [[Portugal|Portuguese]] retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played mainly as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Lubango]], [[Angola]], Z\u00e9 T\u00f3 began his professional career at [[Vit\u00f3ria F.C.|Vit\u00f3ria de Set\u00fabal]], but could never break into the main squad. After a stint in the lower leagues, he first made an impact in the [[Primeira Liga]] with [[S.C. Farense]].\n\nIn the summer of 2000, Z\u00e9 T\u00f3 joined [[Spain]]'s [[UD Salamanca]], a team that also included three compatriots. After a one and a half year on loan to fellow [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|second level]] side [[CD Badajoz]], he returned and began appearing regularly (after only eight league games from August 2000\u2013December 2001), going on to amass 186 official appearances for the former.\n\nAfter an unassuming [[2008\u201309 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2008\u201309 season]] \u2013 five matches, 141 minutes of action \u2013 Z\u00e9 T\u00f3 was released, arranging a deal with another Spanish club, lowly [[AD Cerro de Reyes]], Badajoz's neighbours.<ref>[http://www.esfutbol.net/?action=read&idnotizia=44399 Cerro Reyes: se incorpora Z\u00e9 T\u00f3 (Cerro Reyes: Z\u00e9 T\u00f3 joins)]; esFutbol, 28 July 2009 {{in lang|es}}</ref> However, he quickly grew unsettled, returning to his country after nearly ten years and moving to the regional leagues with [[Estrela de Vendas Novas]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ForaDeJogo}}\n*{{BDFutbol|4397}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ze To}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lubango]]\n[[Category:Twin people from Portugal]]\n[[Category:Twin sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Portuguese footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:Vit\u00f3ria F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Lusitano G.C. players]]\n[[Category:S.C. Farense players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:UD Salamanca players]]\n[[Category:CD Badajoz players]]\n[[Category:Portugal B international footballers]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Portuguese footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Portuguese name|Ramos|Ribeiro}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Z\u00e9 T\u00f3\n| image =\n| fullname = Jos\u00e9 Ant\u00f3nio Ramos Ribeiro\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1977|9|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lubango]], [[Angola]]\n| height = {{height|m=1.80|precision=0}}\n| position = [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthyears2 =\n| youthclubs1 = Pa\u00e7o de Sousa\n| youthclubs2 = [[Vit\u00f3ria F.C.|Vit\u00f3ria Set\u00fabal]]\n| years1 = 1996\u20131997\n| years2 = 1997\u20131999\n| years3 = 1999\u20132000\n| years4 = 2000\u20132009\n| years5 = 2002\u20132003\n| years6 = 2009\n| years7 = 2010\u20132011\n| clubs1 = [[Vit\u00f3ria F.C.|Vit\u00f3ria Set\u00fabal]]\n| clubs2 = [[Lusitano G.C.|Lusitano \u00c9vora]]\n| clubs3 = [[S.C. Farense|Farense]]\n| clubs4 = [[UD Salamanca|Salamanca]]\n| clubs5 = \u2192 [[CD Badajoz|Badajoz]] (loan)\n| clubs6 = [[AD Cerro de Reyes|Cerro Reyes]]\n| clubs7 = [[Estrela de Vendas Novas|Estrela Vendas Novas]]\n| caps1 = 3\n| caps2 =   \n| caps3 = 23\n| caps4 = 179\n| caps5 = 53\n| caps6 = 7\n| caps7 = 26\n| totalcaps = 291\n| goals1 = 0\n| goals2 =  \n| goals3 = 4\n| goals4 = 21\n| goals5 = 8\n| goals6 = 0\n| goals7 = 4\n| totalgoals = 37\n| nationalyears1 = 2000\n| nationalteam1 = [[Portugal national football B team|Portugal B]] \n| nationalcaps1 = 1 \n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| club-update =\n}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 \u00c1nt\u00f3nio Ramos Ribeiro''' (born 11 September 1977), commonly known as '''Z\u00e9 T\u00f3''', is a [[Portugal|Portuguese]] retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played mainly as an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]].\n\n==Football career==\nBorn in [[Lubango]], [[Angola]], Z\u00e9 T\u00f3 began his professional career at [[Vit\u00f3ria F.C.|Vit\u00f3ria de Set\u00fabal]], but could never break into the main squad. After a stint in the lower leagues, he first made an impact in the [[Primeira Liga]] with [[S.C. Farense]].\n\nIn the summer of 2000, Z\u00e9 T\u00f3 joined [[Spain]]'s [[UD Salamanca]], a team that also included three compatriots. After a one-and-a-half year loaned to fellow [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|second level]] side [[CD Badajoz]], he returned and began appearing regularly (after only eight league games from August 2000\u2013December 2001), going on to amass 186 official appearances for the former.\n\nAfter an unassuming [[2008\u201309 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|2008\u201309 season]] \u2013 five matches, 141 minutes of action \u2013 Z\u00e9 T\u00f3 was released, arranging a deal with another Spanish club, lowly [[AD Cerro de Reyes]], Badajoz's neighbours.<ref>[http://www.esfutbol.net/?action=read&idnotizia=44399 Cerro Reyes: se incorpora Z\u00e9 T\u00f3 (Cerro Reyes: Z\u00e9 T\u00f3 joins)]; esFutbol, 28 July 2009 {{in lang|es}}</ref> However, he quickly grew unsettled, returning to his country after nearly ten years and moving to the regional leagues with [[Estrela de Vendas Novas]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ForaDeJogo}}\n*{{BDFutbol|4397}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ze To}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lubango]]\n[[Category:Twin people from Portugal]]\n[[Category:Twin sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Portuguese footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:Vit\u00f3ria F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Lusitano G.C. players]]\n[[Category:S.C. Farense players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:UD Salamanca players]]\n[[Category:CD Badajoz players]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Portugal B international footballers]]\n", "name_user": "Quite A Character", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor tidyups overall, nothing hurt whatsoever.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Z%C3%A9_T%C3%B3"}
{"title_page": "Lincoln Futura", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=June 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Lincoln Futura\n| image = LincolnFutura.jpg\n| caption = 1955 Lincoln Futura\n| aka = \n| manufacturer = [[Lincoln Motor Company|Lincoln]] ([[Ford]])\n| production = 1954<br />one prototype built\n| model_years = 1955\n| assembly = [[Carrozzeria Ghia]], [[Turin]], [[Italy]]\n| designer = [[John Najjar]] and Bill Schmidt\n| class = [[Concept car]]\n| body_style = 2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n| layout = [[Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive]]\n| related =\n| engine = {{convert|368|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Lincoln Y-block V8 engine#368|Y-block]]'' [[Overhead valve engine|OHV]] [[V8 engine|V8]]\n| transmission = 3-speed ''Turbo Drive'' [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|126.0|in|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|227.0|in|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|84.6|in|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|58.2|in|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Specifications - The Futura|url=http://1966batmobile.com/batmobile-feature-the-futura/|website=The Classic 1966 TV Batmobile|accessdate=13 August 2016}}</ref>\n| weight = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| sp = us\n}}\n\nThe '''Lincoln Futura''' is a [[concept car]] promoted by Ford's [[Lincoln (automobile)|Lincoln]] brand, designed by [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]]'s lead [[Automotive stylist|stylist]]s Bill Schmidt and [[John Najjar]],<ref name=\"AutoLife \">{{Cite news | first= Douglas A. |last=Bakken|title= Automotive Design Oral History Project: Remembering John Najjar|url= http://www.autolife.umd.umich.edu/Design/Najjar1_interview.htm | work=[[University of Michigan]]  |accessdate= 22 July 2012  }}</ref><ref name=\"Bryant and Stratton. \">{{Cite news| first= Detroit| last= Prototypes| title= Detroit's Prototype and Concept Vehicles:  1955 Futura| url= http://www.design.bryantstratton.edu/students/ro.thompson.erik/100/project1/ford.html| work= [[Bryant & Stratton College]]| date= n.d.| accessdate= 22 July 2012| url-status= dead| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160307145808/http://design.bryantstratton.edu/students/ro.thompson.erik/100/project1/ford.html| archivedate= 7 March 2016}}</ref> and hand-built by [[Ghia]] in [[Turin]], [[Italy]] &mdash; at a cost of $250,000 (equivalent to ${{inflation|US|250000|1955|r=-5|fmt=c}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}}).\n\nDisplayed on the [[auto show]] circuit in 1955, the Futura was modified by [[George Barris (auto customizer)|George Barris]] into the [[Batmobile#Futura|Batmobile]], for the 1966 TV series ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]''.\n\n==History==\nThe car's official public debut was on 8 January 1955 at the Chicago Auto Show;<ref>\u201cTwo Lincoln-Mercury Firsts at the Chicago Auto Show: World Premiere of the Lincoln Futura\u201d (display ad). 9 January 1955.</ref> it had been shown to the press at the city's Congress Hotel on 5 January.<ref>\u201cExperimental Car Will Be Seen at Show\u201d Chicago Tribune, 6 January 1955.</ref> While being displayed elsewhere in the U.S. that spring, the Futura was seen the country's television audience on [[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]] (\"The Today Show\") on 3 March 1955.<ref>\u201cRadio-TV.\u201d Buffalo Courier-Express, 3 March 1955.</ref>\nThe Futura's styling was original by 1950s standards &mdash; with a double, clear-plastic canopy top, exaggerated hooded [[headlight]] pods, and very large, outward-canted [[Car tailfin|tailfins]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=fNwDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA95 \"Lincoln Shows Its Idea Automobile.\"] ''Popular Mechanics'', March 1955, p. 95.</ref> Nevertheless, the Futura had a complete [[powertrain]] and was fully operable, in contrast to many [[show car]]s. Its original color was white, and was one of the first [[Pearlescent coatings|pearlescent color treatments]], using ground pearl to achieve the paint effect. The Futura was powered by a [[Lincoln Y-block V8 engine#368|368 cubic inch Lincoln engine]] and powertrain; the [[chassis]] derived from a [[Continental Mark II]].{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nThe Futura was a success as a show car, garnering favorable publicity for Ford. It was released as a model kit and a toy, and, in a much more subdued form, its headlight and tailfin motifs would appear on production Lincolns for 1956 and 1957, such as the [[Lincoln Premiere]] and [[Lincoln Capri]]. The concave front grille inspired the grille on the 1960 [[Mercury Monterey#1959\u20131960|Mercury Monterey]] and the 1960 [[Ford Galaxie#1960\u20131964|Ford Galaxie]].{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n==Media appearances==\nThe Futura played a prominent part in the 1959 movie ''[[It Started with a Kiss (film)|It Started with a Kiss]],'' starring [[Debbie Reynolds]] and [[Glenn Ford]]. For the movie, it was painted red, as the white pearlescent finish did not photograph well.<ref>[http://imcdb.org/vehicle_2349-Lincoln-Futura-1955.html 1955 Lincoln Futura in It Started with a Kiss, Movie, 1959] at the Internet Movie Car Database</ref>\n\nThe red-painted car is also seen in Ford's 1961 promotional film \"The Secret Door.\" The film's looking inside Ford's Styling Center includes footage of the Futura on the test track and in the wind tunnel.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9r7wy1k97oo</ref>\n\nThe concept car was subsequently sold to auto customizer [[George Barris (auto customizer)|George Barris]]. Having originally cost $250,000, the Futura was sold to Barris for $1.00 and \"other valuable consideration\" by Ford Motor Company. As the car was never titled and was therefore uninsurable, it was parked behind Barris' shop, sitting idle and deteriorating for several years.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nThe Lincoln Futura was also included in DLC: Vegas Pack of [[Mafia II]] as \"Jefferson Futura\".{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n===Batmobile===\n{{Main|Batmobile#Batman (1960s film/television series)}}\n[[File:1960s Batmobile (FMC).jpg|thumb|right|220px|The [[Batmobile]] from the 1960s ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]' TV series]]\n\nIn 1966 Barris was asked to design a theme car for the ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]'' [[television series]].<ref>George Barris, David Fetherston, ''Barris TV and Movie Cars'', pages 20-27 (MBI Publishing Company, 1996) {{ISBN|0-7603-0198-0}}</ref> Originally the auto stylist [[Dean Jeffries]] was contracted to build the car for the show in late 1965, but when the studio wanted the car sooner than he could deliver, the project was given to Barris.<ref name=StAntoine-MT>St. Antoine, Arthur. - [http://www.motortrend.com/classic/features/c12_0511_dean_jeffries_interview/index.html \"Interview: Dean Jeffries, Hollywood legend\"]. - ''[[Motor Trend|Motor Trend Magazine]]''</ref> With the short notice, Barris thought the Futura might work well, and using Jeffries's initial car, decided that its unusual winged shape would be an ideal starting point for the [[Batmobile]]. Barris hired [[Bill Cushenberry]] to modify the car's metalwork.\nBarris went on to build three fiberglass replicas using the frames and running gear from 1966 [[Ford Galaxie]] cars for the show circuit, three of which were covered with a felt-like flocking finish in the 1970s.  Barris later acquired a fourth replica, a metal car built on a 1958 [[Ford Thunderbird]].{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nBarris retained ownership of the car, both after its conversion to the Batmobile, leasing it to the TV studio for filming and after production of the TV series ended, displayed in Barris' own museum in California. It has also been displayed in the Cayman Motor Museum on [[Grand Cayman]] Island.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nBarris sold the Batmobile to Rick Champagne at the [[Barrett-Jackson]] collector car auction on Saturday, January 19, 2013 in Scottsdale, Arizona for US $4.62 million dollars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barrett-jackson.com/Media/Home/Reader/sold-barrett-jacksons-5000-series-generates-more-than-29-2-million-in-scottsdale?name=sold-barrett-jacksons-5000-series-generates-more-than-29-2-million-in-scottsdale|title=Sold! Barrett-Jackson\u2019s 5000 Series Generates More Than $29.2 Million In Scottsdale |date=January 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Couch|first=Aaron|title=JAN 19 21 MINS First Batmobile Fetches $4.6 Million at Auction|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/first-batmobile-fetches-46-million-413975|publisher=Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/cars/2013/01/20/batmobile-auction-barrett-jackson/1848733/%7caccessdate=2013-01-20 | work=USA Today | title=Original Batmobile from TV series sells for $4.2M | date=20 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Replica ==\n[[Image:1955 Lincoln Futura takenonmycamera November 7th 2009.jpg|thumb|Bob Butts Replica, as seen in Ohio November 7, 2009]]\n\nIn the 1990s, Bob Butts (with George Barris' consent) made replicas of the Batmobiles. He took one of the Barris-built replica Batmobiles and made a mold of it. Based on pictures from when the Futura was shown in the 1950s, he reskinned an existing Batmobile replica back into a Lincoln Futura replica. He only created one copy.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nCurrent{{When|date=June 2017}} toy versions of the Futura Batmobile are being made by Mattel ([[Hot Wheels]]) and [[Polar Lights (models)|Polar Lights models]], among others. Mr. Barris only recently allowed these toys to be made again.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nThe original fiberglas copy Shell of the Futura Made by Bob Butts was later found by Gotham garage owner Mark Towle and his friend and actor Shawn Pilot and rebuild as an original copy of the Lincoln Futura together with his team of friends (Caveman,Constance, and Tony) in their shop in Temecula California, as seen in the Netflix series \u201cCar Masters: Rust to Riches\u201d . (2018)\n\nAfter finishing the Car the Futura was eventually sold at \u201cThe Grand National Roadster Show\u201d at Pomona for approximately  $90.000.- to Keith Dean whose father Dick Dean worked with George Barris.\n\nIn this deal Mark also sold his just finished International COE Car transport truck for $ 90.000.- and got a 1936 Ford with it from Keith Dean that was also part of the deal.\nIn Total the deal was worth approximately $ 250.000.- .(2018) exactly the same amount of money Ford build the original car for in 1954/55.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Ford Futura]]\n* [[Batmobile]]\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080621102904/http://www.javelinamx.com/Batmobile/futura0.htm Designing the Futura]\n* [http://www.1966batmobile.com/background.htm A very comprehensive Futura page]\n* [http://www.1966batmobile.com/toys.htm Futura/Batmobile toys]\n* [http://www.filmmonthly.com/Profiles/Articles/GBarris/GBarris.html George Barris interview]\n* [http://www.volocars.com/attractions-hollywood.html Volo Auto Museum Hollywood collection page]\n* [https://www.thegentlemanracer.com/2013/01/before-batman.html Before Batman the history of the Lincoln Futura]\n{{Lincoln Motor Company}}{{Ford Motor Company}}\n\n[[Category:Lincoln concept vehicles|Futura]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=June 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Lincoln Futura\n| image = LincolnFutura.jpg\n| caption = 1955 Lincoln Futura\n| aka = \n| manufacturer = [[Lincoln Motor Company|Lincoln]] ([[Ford]])\n| production = 1954<br />one prototype built\n| model_years = 1955\n| assembly = [[Carrozzeria Ghia]], [[Turin]], [[Italy]]\n| designer = [[John Najjar]] and Bill Schmidt\n| class = [[Concept car]]\n| body_style = 2-door [[coup\u00e9]]\n| layout = [[Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, rear-wheel-drive]]\n| related =\n| engine = {{convert|368|cuin|L|1|abbr=on}} ''[[Lincoln Y-block V8 engine#368|Y-block]]'' [[Overhead valve engine|OHV]] [[V8 engine|V8]]\n| transmission = 3-speed ''Turbo Drive'' [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]\n| wheelbase = {{convert|126.0|in|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|227.0|in|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|84.6|in|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|58.2|in|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Specifications - The Futura|url=http://1966batmobile.com/batmobile-feature-the-futura/|website=The Classic 1966 TV Batmobile|accessdate=13 August 2016}}</ref>\n| weight = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| sp = us\n}}\n\nThe '''Lincoln Futura''' is a [[concept car]] promoted by Ford's [[Lincoln (automobile)|Lincoln]] brand, designed by [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]]'s lead [[Automotive stylist|stylist]]s Bill Schmidt and [[John Najjar]],<ref name=\"AutoLife \">{{Cite news | first= Douglas A. |last=Bakken|title= Automotive Design Oral History Project: Remembering John Najjar|url= http://www.autolife.umd.umich.edu/Design/Najjar1_interview.htm | work=[[University of Michigan]]  |accessdate= 22 July 2012  }}</ref><ref name=\"Bryant and Stratton. \">{{Cite news| first= Detroit| last= Prototypes| title= Detroit's Prototype and Concept Vehicles:  1955 Futura| url= http://www.design.bryantstratton.edu/students/ro.thompson.erik/100/project1/ford.html| work= [[Bryant & Stratton College]]| date= n.d.| accessdate= 22 July 2012| url-status= dead| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160307145808/http://design.bryantstratton.edu/students/ro.thompson.erik/100/project1/ford.html| archivedate= 7 March 2016}}</ref> and hand-built by [[Ghia]] in [[Turin]], [[Italy]] &mdash; at a cost of $250,000 (equivalent to ${{inflation|US|250000|1955|r=-5|fmt=c}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}}).\n\nDisplayed on the [[auto show]] circuit in 1955, the Futura was modified by [[George Barris (auto customizer)|George Barris]] into the [[Batmobile#Futura|Batmobile]], for the 1966 TV series ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]''.\n\n==History==\nThe car's official public debut was on 8 January 1955 at the Chicago Auto Show;<ref>\u201cTwo Lincoln-Mercury Firsts at the Chicago Auto Show: World Premiere of the Lincoln Futura\u201d (display ad). 9 January 1955.</ref> it had been shown to the press at the city's Congress Hotel on 5 January.<ref>\u201cExperimental Car Will Be Seen at Show\u201d Chicago Tribune, 6 January 1955.</ref> While being displayed elsewhere in the U.S. that spring, the Futura was seen the country's television audience on [[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]] (\"The Today Show\") on 3 March 1955.<ref>\u201cRadio-TV.\u201d Buffalo Courier-Express, 3 March 1955.</ref>\nThe Futura's styling was original by 1950s standards &mdash; with a double, clear-plastic canopy top, exaggerated hooded [[headlight]] pods, and very large, outward-canted [[Car tailfin|tailfins]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=fNwDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA95 \"Lincoln Shows Its Idea Automobile.\"] ''Popular Mechanics'', March 1955, p. 95.</ref> Nevertheless, the Futura had a complete [[powertrain]] and was fully operable, in contrast to many [[show car]]s. Its original color was white, and was one of the first [[Pearlescent coatings|pearlescent color treatments]], using ground pearl to achieve the paint effect. The Futura was powered by a [[Lincoln Y-block V8 engine#368|368 cubic inch Lincoln engine]] and powertrain; the [[chassis]] derived from a [[Continental Mark II]].{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nThe Futura was a success as a show car, garnering favorable publicity for Ford. It was released as a model kit and a toy, and, in a much more subdued form, its headlight and tailfin motifs would appear on production Lincolns for 1956 and 1957, such as the [[Lincoln Premiere]] and [[Lincoln Capri]]. The concave front grille inspired the grille on the 1960 [[Mercury Monterey#1959\u20131960|Mercury Monterey]] and the 1960 [[Ford Galaxie#1960\u20131964|Ford Galaxie]].{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n==Media appearances==\nThe Futura played a prominent part in the 1959 movie ''[[It Started with a Kiss (film)|It Started with a Kiss]],'' starring [[Debbie Reynolds]] and [[Glenn Ford]]. For the movie, it was painted red, as the white pearlescent finish did not photograph well.<ref>[http://imcdb.org/vehicle_2349-Lincoln-Futura-1955.html 1955 Lincoln Futura in It Started with a Kiss, Movie, 1959] at the Internet Movie Car Database</ref>\n\nThe red-painted car is also seen in Ford's 1961 promotional film \"The Secret Door.\" The film's looking inside Ford's Styling Center includes footage of the Futura on the test track and in the wind tunnel.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9r7wy1k97oo</ref>\n\nThe concept car was subsequently sold to auto customizer [[George Barris (auto customizer)|George Barris]]. Having originally cost $250,000, the Futura was sold to Barris for $1.00 and \"other valuable consideration\" by Ford Motor Company. As the car was never titled and was therefore uninsurable, it was parked behind Barris' shop, sitting idle and deteriorating for several years.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nThe Lincoln Futura was also included in DLC: Vegas Pack of [[Mafia II]] as \"Jefferson Futura\".{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n===Batmobile===\n{{Main|Batmobile#Batman (1960s film/television series)}}\n[[File:1960s Batmobile (FMC).jpg|thumb|right|220px|The [[Batmobile]] from the 1960s ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]' TV series]]\n\nIn 1966 Barris was asked to design a theme car for the ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]'' [[television series]].<ref>George Barris, David Fetherston, ''Barris TV and Movie Cars'', pages 20-27 (MBI Publishing Company, 1996) {{ISBN|0-7603-0198-0}}</ref> Originally the auto stylist [[Dean Jeffries]] was contracted to build the car for the show in late 1965, but when the studio wanted the car sooner than he could deliver, the project was given to Barris.<ref name=StAntoine-MT>St. Antoine, Arthur. - [http://www.motortrend.com/classic/features/c12_0511_dean_jeffries_interview/index.html \"Interview: Dean Jeffries, Hollywood legend\"]. - ''[[Motor Trend|Motor Trend Magazine]]''</ref> With the short notice, Barris thought the Futura might work well, and using Jeffries's initial car, decided that its unusual winged shape would be an ideal starting point for the [[Batmobile]]. Barris hired [[Bill Cushenberry]] to modify the car's metalwork.\nBarris went on to build three fiberglass replicas using the frames and running gear from 1966 [[Ford Galaxie]] cars for the show circuit, three of which were covered with a felt-like flocking finish in the 1970s.  Barris later acquired a fourth replica, a metal car built on a 1958 [[Ford Thunderbird]].{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nBarris retained ownership of the car, both after its conversion to the Batmobile, leasing it to the TV studio for filming and after production of the TV series ended, displayed in Barris' own museum in California. It has also been displayed in the Cayman Motor Museum on [[Grand Cayman]] Island.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nBarris sold the Batmobile to Rick Champagne at the [[Barrett-Jackson]] collector car auction on Saturday, January 19, 2013 in Scottsdale, Arizona for US $4.62 million dollars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barrett-jackson.com/Media/Home/Reader/sold-barrett-jacksons-5000-series-generates-more-than-29-2-million-in-scottsdale?name=sold-barrett-jacksons-5000-series-generates-more-than-29-2-million-in-scottsdale|title=Sold! Barrett-Jackson\u2019s 5000 Series Generates More Than $29.2 Million In Scottsdale |date=January 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Couch|first=Aaron|title=JAN 19 21 MINS First Batmobile Fetches $4.6 Million at Auction|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/first-batmobile-fetches-46-million-413975|publisher=Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/cars/2013/01/20/batmobile-auction-barrett-jackson/1848733/%7caccessdate=2013-01-20 | work=USA Today | title=Original Batmobile from TV series sells for $4.2M | date=20 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Replica ==\n[[Image:1955 Lincoln Futura takenonmycamera November 7th 2009.jpg|thumb|Bob Butts Replica, as seen in Ohio November 7, 2009]]\n\nIn the 1990s, Bob Butts (with George Barris' consent) made replicas of the Batmobiles. He took one of the Barris-built replica Batmobiles and made a mold of it. Based on pictures from when the Futura was shown in the 1950s, he reskinned an existing Batmobile replica back into a Lincoln Futura replica. He only created one copy.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nCurrent{{When|date=June 2017}} toy versions of the Futura Batmobile are being made by Mattel ([[Hot Wheels]]) and [[Polar Lights (models)|Polar Lights models]], among others. Mr. Barris only recently allowed these toys to be made again.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\nThe original fiberglas copy Shell of the Futura Made by Bob Butts was later found by Gotham garage owner Mark Towle and his friend and actor Shawn Pilot and rebuild as an original copy of the Lincoln Futura together with his team of friends (Caveman,Constance, and Tony) in their shop in Temecula California, as seen in the Netflix series \u201cCar Masters: Rust to Riches\u201d . (2018)\n\nAfter finishing the Car the Futura was eventually sold at \u201cThe Grand National Roadster Show\u201d at Pomona for approximately  $90.000.- to Keith Dean who\u2019s father Dick Dean worked with George Barris.\n\nIn this deal Mark also sold his just finished International COE Car transport truck for $ 90.000.- and got a 1936 Ford with it from Keith Dean that was also part of the deal.\nIn Total the deal was worth approximately $ 250.000.- .(2018) exactly the same ammount of Money Ford build the original car for in 1954/55.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Ford Futura]]\n* [[Batmobile]]\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080621102904/http://www.javelinamx.com/Batmobile/futura0.htm Designing the Futura]\n* [http://www.1966batmobile.com/background.htm A very comprehensive Futura page]\n* [http://www.1966batmobile.com/toys.htm Futura/Batmobile toys]\n* [http://www.filmmonthly.com/Profiles/Articles/GBarris/GBarris.html George Barris interview]\n* [http://www.volocars.com/attractions-hollywood.html Volo Auto Museum Hollywood collection page]\n* [https://www.thegentlemanracer.com/2013/01/before-batman.html Before Batman the history of the Lincoln Futura]\n{{Lincoln Motor Company}}{{Ford Motor Company}}\n\n[[Category:Lincoln concept vehicles|Futura]]\n", "name_user": "Regicide1649", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReplica:spellings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lincoln_Futura"}
{"title_page": "David W. Whitlock", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific_prefix   = Dr.\n | name               = David W. Whitlock\n | native_name        = <!--The person's name in their own language, if different.-->\n | native_name_lang   = <!--ISO 639-1 code, e.g., \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} in |native_name= instead.-->\n | honorific_suffix   = \n | image              = \n | image_size         = \n | image_upright      = \n | smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n | alt                = \n | caption            = \n | order              = 15th\n | office             = President of Oklahoma Baptist University\n | status             = <!--If this is specified, overrides Incumbent.-->\n | term_start         = November 1, 2008\n | term_end           = <!-- Add data only when the actual term has ended, not for terms which will end in the future. (Per usage guideline.) -->January 8, 2019\n | alongside          = <!--For two or more people serving in the same position from the same district.  (e.g. United States Senators.)-->\n | monarch            = \n | president          = \n | governor_general   = \n | primeminister      = \n | taoiseach          = \n | chancellor         = \n | governor           = \n | chair              = \n | vicepresident      = \n | viceprimeminister  = \n | deputy             = \n | lieutenant         = \n | vicechair          = \n | succeeding         = <!--For President-elect or equivalent-->\n | parliamentarygroup = \n | constituency       = \n | majority           = \n | predecessor        = [[John W. Parrish]]\n | successor          = \n | prior_term         = \n | order2             =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | office2            =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | term_start2        =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | term_end2          =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | alongside2         =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | monarch2           =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | president2         =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | governor_general2  =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | primeminister2     =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | chancellor2        =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | taoiseach2         =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | governor2          =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | chair2             =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | vicepresident2     =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | viceprimeminister2 =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | deputy2            =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | lieutenant2        =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | vicechair2         =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | succeeding2        =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | predecessor2       =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | successor2         =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | parliamentarygroup2=  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | constituency2      =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | majority2          =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | prior_term2        =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n}}\n\n'''Dr. David Wesley Whitlock''' was the 15th president of [[Oklahoma Baptist University]]. He served as president from November 1, 2008 to January 8, 2019. A longtime college administrator and faculty member, Whitlock was noted for his emphasis on the integration of faith and learning.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.okbu.edu/about/president/staff/david_whitlock.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-02-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228093028/http://www.okbu.edu/about/president/staff/david_whitlock.html |archive-date=2009-02-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nA fifth-generation Oklahoman, Whitlock was born in [[Purcell, Oklahoma|Purcell]] and graduated from Wayne High School in [[Wayne, Oklahoma]]. He completed a bachelor's degree in chemistry from [[Southeastern Oklahoma State University]] in 1984, a master of business administration from Southeastern in 1985, and a doctorate in educational leadership and policy studies from the [[University of Oklahoma]] in 1995.<ref>http://www.news-star.com/education/x565954056/OBU-prepares-to-celebrate-100-years</ref>  Whitlock had served as associate provost at SBU since 2006, a position responsible for accreditation activities with the [[Higher Learning Commission]] of the [[North Central Association of Colleges and Schools]]. Whitlock aided in SBU\u2019s 10-year review process for continued accreditation during the 2005-06 school year. In 2007, Whitlock was appointed dean of SBU\u2019s adult and off-campus programs. From 2001 to 2006, he served as assistant to SBU President [[C. Pat Taylor]] for strategic planning.<ref>http://newsok.com/whitlock-to-head-oklahoma-bapist-university/article/3309866</ref>  \nWhitlock has played an active role in international programs and missions endeavors, working with educational organizations in the [[United Arab Emirates]], [[China]] and [[Russia]]. He has traveled extensively visiting, serving on mission teams, or leading educational tours in thirty countries.  Active in a variety of professional organizations, Whitlock has served as a consultant-evaluator with the [[Higher Learning Commission]] of the [[North Central Association of Colleges and Schools]] since 2006. He also is an evaluator and mentor with the [[Association of Collegiate Business Schools and Programs]].\n\n==Employment history==\nWhitlock had been associate [[Provost (education)|provost]], dean of graduate studies, and dean of the college of business and computer science at [[Southwest Baptist University]] in [[Bolivar, Missouri]]. He joined the SBU administration in 1999, and also was a professor of business at the Missouri Baptist institution. Prior to his work at SBU, he taught for 14 years at [[Southeastern Oklahoma State University]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abpnews.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3569&Itemid=53 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-03-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081019181505/http://www.abpnews.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3569&Itemid=53 |archive-date=2008-10-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was appointed to the Southeastern faculty in 1985 as an instructor of business. He was promoted to assistant professor in 1991 and associate professor in 1996. He was named chair of the university\u2019s business information management program in 1995 and served in that role until moving to SBU.<ref>http://www.baptiststandard.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=8646&Itemid=53</ref> In addition to his academic work, Whitlock served as a bivocational co-pastor of Wellspring Baptist Fellowship in Bolivar, Missouri, from 1999 until his move to OBU in 2008. He was bivocational pastor of Silo Baptist Church in [[Silo, Oklahoma|Silo]], Oklahoma, from 1996 to 1999, and Hendrix Baptist Church in [[Hendrix, Oklahoma]], from 1993 to 1994. He was licensed to preach by the First Baptist Church of [[Durant, Oklahoma|Durant]] and ordained at Hendrix Baptist Church.\n\n==Retirement==\nOn January 8, 2019, Whitlock announced his retirement as OBU president. He served the rest of the academic year as chancellor. <ref>[https://www.okbu.edu/news/2019/01/obu-president-david-w.-whitlock-announces-retirement.html \"OBU President David W. Whitlock Announces Retirement.\" Oklahoma Baptist University. Press Release. January 8, 2019.] Accessed 28 February 2020.</ref> \n\n==Author==\nWhitlock is the author of the book ''Opportunity: Introducing Free Enterprise and Business''.<ref>http://wipfandstock.com/store/Opportunity_Introducing_Free_Enterprise_and_Business</ref> He has been co-author or editor of three books related to business: ''A Noble Calling: Devotions and Essays for Business Professionals'';<ref>http://wipfandstock.com/store/A_Noble_Calling_Devotions_and_Essays_for_Business_Professionals</ref> ''Psalm 15: Integrating Life and Work'';<ref>http://wipfandstock.com/store/Psalm_15_Integrating_Faith_and_Work</ref> and ''Solomon Was a Businessman: Advice from the Wealthiest Man on Earth''.<ref>http://wipfandstock.com/store/Solomon_was_a_Businessman_Advice_from_the_Wealthiest_Man_on_Earth</ref> He also has been a contributing writer for numerous other works.\n\n==Education==\n[[B.S.]] [[Chemistry]], [[Southeastern Oklahoma State University]]\n\n[[MBA]], [[Southeastern Oklahoma State University]]\n\n[[Ph.D.]], [[University of Oklahoma]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Oklahoma Baptist University presidents}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitlock, David}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Purcell, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:American clergy]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Southeastern Oklahoma State University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Oklahoma alumni]]\n[[Category:Southeastern Oklahoma State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Southern Baptist ministers]]\n[[Category:Southwest Baptist University faculty]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Oklahoma Baptist University]]\n[[Category:People from Bolivar, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n | honorific_prefix   = Dr.\n | name               = David W. Whitlock\n | native_name        = <!--The person's name in their own language, if different.-->\n | native_name_lang   = <!--ISO 639-1 code, e.g., \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} in |native_name= instead.-->\n | honorific_suffix   = \n | image              = \n | image_size         = \n | image_upright      = \n | smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n | alt                = \n | caption            = \n | order              = 15th\n | office             = President of Oklahoma Baptist University\n | status             = <!--If this is specified, overrides Incumbent.-->\n | term_start         = November 1, 2008\n | term_end           = <!-- Add data only when the actual term has ended, not for terms which will end in the future. (Per usage guideline.) -->January 8, 2019\n | alongside          = <!--For two or more people serving in the same position from the same district.  (e.g. United States Senators.)-->\n | monarch            = \n | president          = \n | governor_general   = \n | primeminister      = \n | taoiseach          = \n | chancellor         = \n | governor           = \n | chair              = \n | vicepresident      = \n | viceprimeminister  = \n | deputy             = \n | lieutenant         = \n | vicechair          = \n | succeeding         = <!--For President-elect or equivalent-->\n | parliamentarygroup = \n | constituency       = \n | majority           = \n | predecessor        = [[John W. Parrish]]\n | successor          = \n | prior_term         = \n | order2             =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | office2            =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | term_start2        =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | term_end2          =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | alongside2         =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | monarch2           =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | president2         =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | governor_general2  =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | primeminister2     =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | chancellor2        =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | taoiseach2         =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | governor2          =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | chair2             =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | vicepresident2     =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | viceprimeminister2 =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | deputy2            =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | lieutenant2        =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | vicechair2         =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | succeeding2        =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | predecessor2       =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | successor2         =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | parliamentarygroup2=  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | constituency2      =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | majority2          =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n | prior_term2        =  <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by changing the number-->\n}}\n\n'''Dr. David Wesley Whitlock''' is the 15th president of [[Oklahoma Baptist University]]. He began NGOs term on November 1, 2008. A longtime college administrator and faculty member, Whitlock is noted for his emphasis on the integration of faith and learning.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.okbu.edu/about/president/staff/david_whitlock.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-02-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228093028/http://www.okbu.edu/about/president/staff/david_whitlock.html |archive-date=2009-02-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nWhitlock announced his retirement as president on January 8, 2019, and said that he would remain as chancellor until May 31, 2019 to help maintain an orderly transfer.\n\n==Background==\nA fifth-generation Oklahoman, Whitlock was born in [[Purcell, Oklahoma|Purcell]] and graduated from Wayne High School in [[Wayne, Oklahoma]]. He completed a bachelor's degree in chemistry from [[Southeastern Oklahoma State University]] in 1984, a master of business administration from Southeastern in 1985, and a doctorate in educational leadership and policy studies from the [[University of Oklahoma]] in 1995.<ref>http://www.news-star.com/education/x565954056/OBU-prepares-to-celebrate-100-years</ref>  Whitlock had served as associate provost at SBU since 2006, a position responsible for accreditation activities with the [[Higher Learning Commission]] of the [[North Central Association of Colleges and Schools]]. Whitlock aided in SBU\u2019s 10-year review process for continued accreditation during the 2005-06 school year. In 2007, Whitlock was appointed dean of SBU\u2019s adult and off-campus programs. From 2001 to 2006, he served as assistant to SBU President [[C. Pat Taylor]] for strategic planning.<ref>http://newsok.com/whitlock-to-head-oklahoma-bapist-university/article/3309866</ref>  \nWhitlock has played an active role in international programs and missions endeavors, working with educational organizations in the [[United Arab Emirates]], [[China]] and [[Russia]]. He has traveled extensively visiting, serving on mission teams, or leading educational tours in thirty countries.  Active in a variety of professional organizations, Whitlock has served as a consultant-evaluator with the [[Higher Learning Commission]] of the [[North Central Association of Colleges and Schools]] since 2006. He also is an evaluator and mentor with the [[Association of Collegiate Business Schools and Programs]].\n\n==Employment history==\nWhitlock had been associate [[Provost (education)|provost]], dean of graduate studies, and dean of the college of business and computer science at [[Southwest Baptist University]] in [[Bolivar, Missouri]]. He joined the SBU administration in 1999, and also was a professor of business at the Missouri Baptist institution. Prior to his work at SBU, he taught for 14 years at [[Southeastern Oklahoma State University]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abpnews.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3569&Itemid=53 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-03-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081019181505/http://www.abpnews.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3569&Itemid=53 |archive-date=2008-10-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was appointed to the Southeastern faculty in 1985 as an instructor of business. He was promoted to assistant professor in 1991 and associate professor in 1996. He was named chair of the university\u2019s business information management program in 1995 and served in that role until moving to SBU.<ref>http://www.baptiststandard.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=8646&Itemid=53</ref> In addition to his academic work, Whitlock served as a bivocational co-pastor of Wellspring Baptist Fellowship in Bolivar, Missouri, from 1999 until his move to OBU in 2008. He was bivocational pastor of Silo Baptist Church in [[Silo, Oklahoma|Silo]], Oklahoma, from 1996 to 1999, and Hendrix Baptist Church in [[Hendrix, Oklahoma]], from 1993 to 1994. He was licensed to preach by the First Baptist Church of [[Durant, Oklahoma|Durant]] and ordained at Hendrix Baptist Church.\n\n==Retirement==\nOn January 8, 2019, Whitlock announced that he planned to retire as OBU president on that day, and serve the rest of the academic year as chancellor to help assure the university an orderly transition. His employment at the school would end May 31, 2019.<ref>[https://www.okbu.edu/news/2019/01/obu-president-david-w.-whitlock-announces-retirement.html \"OBU President David W. Whitlock Announces Retirement.\" Oklahoma Baptist University. Press Release. January 8, 2019.] Accessed 28 February 2020.</ref> \n\n==Author==\nWhitlock is the author of the book ''Opportunity: Introducing Free Enterprise and Business''.<ref>http://wipfandstock.com/store/Opportunity_Introducing_Free_Enterprise_and_Business</ref> He has been co-author or editor of three books related to business: ''A Noble Calling: Devotions and Essays for Business Professionals'';<ref>http://wipfandstock.com/store/A_Noble_Calling_Devotions_and_Essays_for_Business_Professionals</ref> ''Psalm 15: Integrating Life and Work'';<ref>http://wipfandstock.com/store/Psalm_15_Integrating_Faith_and_Work</ref> and ''Solomon Was a Businessman: Advice from the Wealthiest Man on Earth''.<ref>http://wipfandstock.com/store/Solomon_was_a_Businessman_Advice_from_the_Wealthiest_Man_on_Earth</ref> He also has been a contributing writer for numerous other works.\n\n==Education==\n[[B.S.]] [[Chemistry]], [[Southeastern Oklahoma State University]]\n\n[[MBA]], [[Southeastern Oklahoma State University]]\n\n[[Ph.D.]], [[University of Oklahoma]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Oklahoma Baptist University presidents}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitlock, David}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Purcell, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:American clergy]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Southeastern Oklahoma State University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Oklahoma alumni]]\n[[Category:Southeastern Oklahoma State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Southern Baptist ministers]]\n[[Category:Southwest Baptist University faculty]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Oklahoma Baptist University]]\n[[Category:People from Bolivar, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Nativeoklahoman", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated to reflect the retirement of David Whitlock.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_W._Whitlock"}
{"title_page": "The Polar Express (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2004 animated film directed by Robert Zemeckis}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name          = The Polar Express\n| image         = Polar express.jpg\n| caption       = Theatrical release poster\n| director      = [[Robert Zemeckis]]\n| producer      = {{plainlist|\n* [[Steve Starkey]]\n* Robert Zemeckis\n* [[Gary Goetzman]]\n* William Teitler\n}}\n| based on       = {{based on|''[[The Polar Express]]''|[[Chris Van Allsburg]]}}\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* Robert Zemeckis\n* [[William Broyles Jr.]]\n}}\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Tom Hanks]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Alan Silvestri]] <!-- Only list composers. -->\n| cinematography = {{plainlist|\n* [[Don Burgess (cinematographer)|Don Burgess]]\n* Robert Presley \n}}\n| editing        = {{plainlist|\n* R. Orlando Duenas\n* Jeremiah O'Driscoll\n}}\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* [[Castle Rock Entertainment]]<ref name=afi>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/members//catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=63194|title=The Polar Express|work=[[American Film Institute]]|accessdate=2016-12-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140403000913/http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=63194|archive-date=April 3, 2014|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Shangri-La Entertainment]]<ref name=afi/>\n* [[ImageMovers]]<ref name=afi/>\n* [[Playtone]]<ref name=afi/>\n* [[Golden Mean]]<ref name=afi/>\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]<ref name=afi/>\n| released       = {{Film date|2004|11|07|[[Chicago International Film Festival|Chicago International<br>Film Festival]]|2004|11|10|United States}}\n| runtime        = 100 minutes<ref name=mojo>{{cite web| url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt0338348/| publisher=Box Office Mojo| title=The Polar Express| accessdate=January 7, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001031835/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=polarexpress.htm| archive-date=October 1, 2007| url-status=live| df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $165 million<ref name=\"mojo\"/><ref>{{cite web| last=Grover| first=Ronald| title=Can Polar Express Make the Grade?| url=http://www.businessweek.com/bwdaily/dnflash/oct2004/nf20041020_7624_db011.htm| work=[[Bloomberg BusinessWeek]]| date=19 October 2001| accessdate=2014-11-12| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091214171051/http://www.businessweek.com/bwdaily/dnflash/oct2004/nf20041020_7624_db011.htm| archive-date=December 14, 2009| url-status=live| df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| gross          = $286 million<ref name=\"mojo weekly\"/><br>(original release)<br>$313.5 million<ref name=\"mojo\"/><br>(all releases)\n}}\n'''''The Polar Express''''' is a 2004 American [[computer-animated]] [[adventure film]]<ref name=afi/> based on the [[The Polar Express|1985 children's book of the same name]] by [[Chris Van Allsburg]], who also served as one of the [[executive producer]]s on the film. Co-written, co-produced and directed by [[Robert Zemeckis]], the film features human characters animated using live-action [[motion capture]] animation. The film tells the story of a young boy who, on [[Christmas Eve]], sees a mysterious train bound for the [[North Pole]] stop outside his window and is invited aboard by its conductor. The boy joins several other children as they embark on a journey to visit Santa Claus preparing for Christmas. The film stars [[Tom Hanks]], who was also one of the film's executive producers, in multiple distinct roles, with [[Daryl Sabara]], [[Nona Gaye]], [[Jimmy Bennett]] and [[Eddie Deezen]] in supporting roles. The film also includes a performance by [[Tinashe]] at age 9, as the [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] model for the female protagonist.\n\n[[Castle Rock Entertainment]] produced the film in association with [[Shangri-La Entertainment]], [[ImageMovers]], [[Playtone]] and Golden Mean Productions for [[Warner Bros. Pictures]], as Castle Rock's first animated film. The visual effects and performance capture were done at [[Sony Pictures Imageworks]]. The film was made with a production budget of $165 million, a record-breaking sum for an animated feature at the time.\n\n''The Polar Express'' was released in both conventional and [[IMAX|IMAX 3D]] theaters on November 10, 2004. The film grossed $311.3 million worldwide, and was later listed in the 2006 ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' as the first all-digital capture film. It also marks [[Michael Jeter]]'s last acting role before his death, and the film was thus dedicated to his memory.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rooney|first1=David|title=Review: 'The Polar Express'|url=https://variety.com/2004/film/reviews/the-polar-express-3-1200530031/|access-date=December 10, 2014|work=Variety|date=October 24, 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226224253/http://variety.com/2004/film/reviews/the-polar-express-3-1200530031/|archive-date=December 26, 2014|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, the plot summary should be 400-700 words. -->\nIn [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]], on the night of Christmas Eve, a boy becomes skeptical of the existence of Santa Claus. Struggling to fall asleep, he witnesses a steam locomotive arrive on the street, and goes outside to examine it. The conductor introduces the train as the Polar Express, bound for the North Pole. Initially reluctant, the boy jumps aboard as the train departs.\n\nIn a passenger car, he meets a spirited girl and a know-it-all boy. The train picks up a boy named Billy, who also declines to board, but changes his mind, and the boy applies the brakes to allow Billy to board, which is noticed by the conductor. As Billy sits alone in the train's [[observation car]], hot chocolate is served in the passenger car, and the girl stows away a cup for Billy. As she and the conductor cross to the dining car, the boy notices that she left her unpunched ticket, but loses hold of the ticket between the cars when he attempts to return it. The ticket reenters the passenger car, but not before the conductor notices its absence and escorts the girl back to the rear car.\n\nWhen the know-it-all claims the conductor will throw the girl from the train, the boy recovers the ticket and dashes to the dining car in search of the conductor, climbing onto the roof. He meets a hobo camping on the roof, who offers him coffee and discusses the existence of Santa Claus and ghosts. The hobo skis with the boy along the tops of the cars toward the [[tender (rail)|coal tender]], where the hobo disappears right at Flat Top Tunnel. In the locomotive's cab, the boy discovers that the girl has been made to supervise driving the train while the engineers Steamer and Smokey replace the headlight. The boy applies the brakes and the train stops coming across a herd of [[caribou]] blocking the tracks. The conductor pulls Smokey's beard, causing him to let out animal-like noises, and the caribou herd strolls away. The train continues on at extreme speed, and the throttle's [[split pin]] (cotter pin) shears off, causing the train to accelerate uncontrollably down a 179-degree grade and onto a frozen lake. Smokey uses his hairpin to repair the throttle as the train drifts across the ice to realign with the tracks moments before the ice breaks. The boy returns the girl's ticket for the conductor to punch, and as the three return to the passenger car, where the boy is taunted by an [[Ebenezer Scrooge]] [[Marionette|marionette puppet]] controlled by the hobo.\n\nThe train arrives at the North Pole, where the conductor announces that one of the passengers will be chosen to receive the first gift of Christmas from Santa himself. Discovering Billy still alone in the observation car, the girl and boy persuade him to come along, but the boy accidentally uncouples the car, sending it back along the line to a [[railway turntable]] in Santa's workshop. The children make their way through an elf command center and a gift sorting office before being dumped into a giant sack of presents, where they discover that the know-it-all has stowed away, and the elves escort them out as Santa arrives. A bell flies loose from the galloping reindeer's reins; the boy initially cannot hear it ring, until he finds it within himself to believe. He shows the bell to Santa, who selects him to receive the first gift of Christmas. Santa agrees to let him keep the bell, and the boy places it in his robe pocket.\n\nThe rear car is returned to the train as the children board to return home, but the boy discovers that he lost the bell through the hole in his pocket. He returns home and awakens Christmas morning to find a present containing the bell. He and his younger sister Sarah joyfully ring the bell, while their parents, not believing in Santa, lament that the bell is broken. The boy reflects on his friends and sister growing deaf to the bell as their belief faded. However, the bell still rings for him, as it will \"for all who truly believe\".\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Michael Jeter at the 44th Emmy Awards cropped.jpg|175px|right|thumb|This film marks the final performance of actor [[Michael Jeter]]; Jeter died the year before the film's release.]]\n{{div col}}\n*[[Tom Hanks]] as Hero Boy {{ref|mocap|I}}, Hero Boy's father, Conductor, Hobo, [[Ebenezer Scrooge|Scrooge]] puppet, Santa Claus, and the Narrator\n**[[Daryl Sabara]] as Hero Boy {{ref|voice|IV}}\n**[[Josh Hutcherson]] as Hero Boy {{ref|ad-mocap|II}}\n*Leslie Zemeckis as Sister Sarah {{ref|mocap|I}} and Hero Boy's mother\n**Isabella Peregrina as Sister Sarah {{ref|voice|IV}}\n**Ashly Holloway as Sister Sarah {{ref|ad-mocap|II}}\n*[[Eddie Deezen]] as Know-It-All\n**[[Jimmy 'Jax' Pinchak]] as Know-It-All {{ref|ad-mocap|II}}\n*[[Nona Gaye]] as Hero Girl\n**Chantel Valdivieso as Hero Girl {{ref|ad-mocap|II}}\n**Meagan Moore as Hero Girl {{ref|singing|V}}\n**[[Tinashe]] as Hero Girl {{ref|model-mocap|III}}\n*[[Peter Scolari]] as Billy the Lonely Boy {{ref|mocap|I}}\n**Hayden McFarland as Billy the Lonely Boy {{ref|ad-mocap|II}}\n**[[Jimmy Bennett]] as Billy the Lonely Boy {{ref|voice|IV}}\n**[[Matthew Hall (actor)|Matthew Hall]] as Billy the Lonely Boy {{ref|singing|V}}\n*[[Dylan Cash]] as Boy on Train {{ref|voice|IV}}\n*Brendan King and Andy Pellick as Pastry Chefs\n*Josh Eli, Rolandas Hendricks, [[Jon Scott]], Sean Scott, Mark Mendonca, [[Mark Goodman]], Gregory Gast, and Gordon Hart as Waiters\n*[[Michael Jeter]] as Smokey and Steamer {{ref|mocap|I}}\n**[[Andr\u00e9 Sogliuzzo]] as Smokey and Steamer {{ref|voice|IV}}\n*[[Chris Coppola]] as Gus the Toothless Boy and an Elf\n**Connor Matheus as Toothless Boy {{ref|ad-mocap|II}}\n*Julene Renee as Red Head Girl and an Elf\n*[[Phil Fondacaro]], [[Debbie Lee Carrington]], [[Mark Povinelli]], and Ed Gale as Elves\n*[[Charles Fleischer]] as Elf General\n*[[Steven Tyler]] as Elf Lieutenant and Elf Singer\n{{div col end}}\n*{{note|mocap|}} '''I''' [[Motion-capture]] only, {{note|ad-mocap|}} '''II''' Additional motion-capture, {{note|model-mocap|}} '''III''' Motion-capture modeling, {{note|voice|}} '''IV''' Voice only, {{note|singing|}} '''V''' Singing voice only\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nHanks optioned the book in 1999 with the hopes of playing the conductor and Santa Claus.<ref name=riding>{{cite web |title=Riding the Polar Express |url=https://www.wired.com/2004/11/riding-the-polar-express/ |website=Wired |accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref> One of the conditions of the sale was that the resulting film not be animated. Zemeckis, however, felt that a live-action version was unfeasible, claiming that it \"would look awful, and it would be impossible \u2013 it would cost $1 billion instead of $160 million.\"<ref name=\"BBCinterview\">{{cite web |last1=Anwar |first1=Bret |title=Robert Zemeckis interview |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2004/12/01/robert_zemeckis_the_polar_express_interview.shtml |website=BBC |accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref> Zemeckis felt that such a version would rob the audience of the art style of the book which he felt was \"so much a part of the emotion of the story\".<ref name=riding/> In order to keep his vision a new process was created by which actors would be filmed with [[motion capturing]] equipment in a black box stage which would then be animated to make the resulting film.<ref name=riding/> Hanks stated that this method of working was \"actually a return to a type of acting that acting in films does not allow you to do\", comparing the process to performing a play [[Theatre in the round|in the round]].<ref name=\"IGNhanks\"/>\n\nHanks plays five roles in the film including that of a small child (whose voice would later be dubbed in by [[Daryl Sabara]]).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Debkzak |first1=Michele |title=8 Festive Facts About The Polar Express |url=https://www.mentalfloss.com/article/567459/the-polar-express-tom-hanks-movie-facts |website=Mental Floss |accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref> Initially Zemeckis considered having him play every role, but after trying this, Hanks grew exhausted, and they whittled down the number.<ref name=\"IGNhanks\">{{cite web |last1=Otto |first1=Jeff |title=Interview: Tom Hanks |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2004/11/10/interview-tom-hanks |website=IGN |accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] of the motion-captures sequences began on June 2003, and [[Wrap (filmmaking)|wrapped]] in May 2004.<ref>{{cite web|title='The Polar Express' Diary: Part 3 -- The MoCap/Anim Process|url=https://www.awn.com/vfxworld/polar-express-diary-part-3-mocapanim-process|accessdate=January 7, 2020|publisher=[[Animation World Network]]}}</ref>\n\n===Architecture===\n[[File:Pullman Chicago Clock Tower.jpg|thumb|Administration building of the Pullman Palace Car Company]]\nThe buildings at the North Pole refer to a number of buildings related to American [[railroading]] history.  The buildings in the square at the city's center are loosely based on the [[Pullman Company|Pullman Factory]] in Chicago's [[Pullman, Chicago|Pullman]] neighborhood.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ridin' the reels|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2007-10-07/news/0710050583_1_beloved-train-great-train-robbery-20th-century-limited/2|accessdate=November 8, 2017|publisher=The Chicago Tribune|date=October 7, 2007|page=2|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170811142932/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2007-10-07/news/0710050583_1_beloved-train-great-train-robbery-20th-century-limited/2|archive-date=August 11, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Polar Express Locomotive===\n[[File:PM1225.jpg|thumb|Pere Marquette locomotive 1225, the basis for the Polar Express.]]\nThe locomotive featured in the film is an American [[2-8-4]] Berkshire type steam locomotive, with a [[cowcatcher]], modeled after the [[Pere Marquette 1225]], which had spent many years on static display near [[Spartan Stadium, East Lansing|Spartan Stadium]] in [[East Lansing, Michigan]] on the campus of Michigan State University, where [[Chris Van Allsburg]] recalled playing on the engine when attending football games as a child.<ref>Detroit Free Press, November 4, 2004 \"Meet Chris Van Allsburg\"</ref>\n\nIn July 2002, [[Warner Bros.]] approached the engine's owner, the [[Steam Railroading Institute]], to study the engine.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steam Railroading Institute History|url=http://www.mstrp.com/history.php|publisher=Steam Railroading Institute|accessdate=August 23, 2015|quote=July 2002: Warner Brothers arranges to use 1225\u2019s image in \u201cThe Polar Express,\u201d...|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150107034108/http://www.mstrp.com/history.php|archive-date=January 7, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The engine in the film is modeled from the PM #1225's drawings and the sounds from recordings made of the 1225 operating under steam.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mills|first1=Rick|title=Iconic steam engine offering rides from Mt. Pleasant|url=http://www.themorningsun.com/general-news/20150522/iconic-steam-engine-offering-rides-from-mt-pleasant|accessdate=August 23, 2015|work=The Morning Sun|date=May 22, 2015|quote=The 1225\u2019s blueprints were used as the prototype for the locomotive image, and its sounds were used to bring the Polar Express to life.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150808014118/http://www.themorningsun.com/general-news/20150522/iconic-steam-engine-offering-rides-from-mt-pleasant|archive-date=August 8, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The whistle, however, was taken from [[Sierra No. 3|Sierra Railway #3]].{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Main|The Polar Express (soundtrack)}}\nThe soundtrack of the film was released on November 2, 2004, through [[Warner Sunset Records]].<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r714374|pure_url=yes}} \"The Polar Express - Original Soundtrack\"]. AllMusic.com. Retrieved 7 January 2020.</ref>\n\n==Release==\n===IMAX 3D version===\nIn addition to standard theatrical 35mm format, a [[3D film|3D]] version for [[IMAX]] was also released, generated from the same 3D digital models used for the standard version.<ref>{{cite journal |last=B. |first=Brian |title=The Polar Express In IMAX 3D Returns to Theaters This Holiday Season |url=https://movieweb.com/the-polar-express-in-imax-3d-returns-to-theaters-this-holiday-season/ |date=November 23, 2011 |access-date=December 15, 2017 |journal=[[MovieWeb]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171204171053/https://movieweb.com/the-polar-express-in-imax-3d-returns-to-theaters-this-holiday-season/ |archive-date=December 4, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nThe film was released on [[DVD]] as separated [[widescreen]] and full-screen versions in single and two-disc special editions (with bonus features) and on [[VHS]] on November 22, 2005, one year after the film came out.<ref>amazon.com, \"[https://www.amazon.com/The-Polar-Express-VHS-Hanks/dp/B000A468XY The Polar Express (VHS)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305171137/http://www.amazon.com/The-Polar-Express-VHS-Hanks/dp/B000A468XY |date=March 5, 2016 }}\". Accessed December 20, 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Thomas|last=Arnold|url=http://hive4media.com/news/html/breaking_article.cfm?article_id=7927|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051014014404/http://hive4media.com:80/news/html/breaking_article.cfm?article_id=7927|title=Warner's 'Polar' Pricing Aimed at Goosing Margins|website=[[hive4media.com]]|archivedate=October 14, 2005|date=August 25, 2005|accessdate=September 22, 2019}}</ref> It was released on [[HD-DVD]] with bonus features in 2006 and on [[Blu-ray]] with bonus features on October 30, 2007, both presented in the original widescreen [[aspect ratio (image)|aspect ratio]].\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\nThe film opened at #2 and earned $23,323,463 from approximately 7,000 screens at 3,650 theaters, for a per-theater average of $6,390 and a per-screen average of $3,332 in its opening weekend. It also brought in a total of $30,629,146 since its Wednesday launch. The weekend total also included $2,100,000 from 59 [[IMAX]] theaters, for an IMAX theater average of $35,593, and had a $3,000,000 take since Wednesday. In its second weekend, the film dropped 33%, and grossing $15,668,101, averaging $4,293 from 3,650 venues and boosting the 12-day cumulative gross to $51,463,282. In its third weekend, which was Thanksgiving weekend, the film increased by 24%, earning $19,389,927, averaging $5,312 from 3,650 venues and raising the 19-day cumulative gross to $81,479,861.<ref name=\"mojo weekly\">{{cite web| url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=polarexpress.htm| publisher=Box Office Mojo| title=The Polar Express - Weekly| accessdate=2019-08-31}}</ref> The film has made $187,224,490 domestically, and $126,275,943 overseas for a total worldwide gross of $313,500,433 (including all re-releases).<ref name=mojo/> It appeared at No. 3 in the \"25 Highest-Grossing Christmas Movies of All Time at the U.S. Box Office\" list by ''[[Forbes]]'', placed after ''[[Home Alone]]'' and ''[[How the Grinch Stole Christmas (2000 film)|How the Grinch Stole Christmas]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 25 Highest-Grossing Christmas Movies Of All Time At The U.S. Box Office|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/simonthompson/2016/11/27/the-25-highest-grossing-christmas-movies-of-all-time-at-the-u-s-box-office/|accessdate=January 7, 2020|publisher=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>\n\nThe film had its network television premiere on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] on December 1, 2006. The airing brought in 13.2 million viewers, winning its timeslot and ranking 20th in the Nielsen ratings that week, according to TVTango.com.\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Metacritic]], the film has a [[weighted average]] score of 61 out of 100 based on 36 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-polar-express|title=The Polar Express|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=2015-06-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627220736/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-polar-express|archive-date=June 27, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an [[approval rating]] of 56% based on 207 reviews, with an average score of 6.42/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"Though the movie is visually stunning overall, the animation for the human characters isn't lifelike enough, and the story is padded.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/polar_express/|title=The Polar Express (2005)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=March 17, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150612123723/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/polar_express/|archive-date=June 12, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''[[The Independent]]'' reported in 2011 that the film \"is now seen by many as a classic\".<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite web| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/the-175m-flop-so-bad-it-could-end-the-3d-boom-2247778.html| title=The 175m flop so bad it could end the 3D boom| work=The Independent| date=21 March 2011| accessdate=2014-11-12| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022084929/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/the-175m-flop-so-bad-it-could-end-the-3d-boom-2247778.html| archive-date=October 22, 2017| url-status=live| df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[CinemaScore]] reported that audiences gave the film a rare \"A+\" grade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/why-cinemascore-matters-box-office-225563|title=Why CinemaScore Matters for Box Office|author=Pamela McClintock|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=August 19, 2011|accessdate=September 14, 2016|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6PTUrtDVN?url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/why-cinemascore-matters-box-office-225563|archive-date=May 10, 2014|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] gave the film his highest rating of four stars, saying: \"There's a deeper, shivery tone, instead of the mindless jolliness of the usual Christmas movie\", and \"it has a haunting, magical quality\". Acknowledging comments by other reviewers, Ebert said, \"It's a little creepy. Not creepy in an unpleasant way, but in that sneaky, teasing way that lets you know eerie things could happen.\"<ref name=ebert>{{cite web| url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-polar-express-2004| title=The Polar Express| publisher=Roger Ebert Reviews| last=Ebert| first=Roger| date=November 9, 2004| accessdate=2014-11-12| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204020816/http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-polar-express-2004| archive-date=December 4, 2013| url-status=live| df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] and [[Mick LaSalle]] also gave highly positive reviews to the film, saying that it \"remains true to the book, right down to the bittersweet final image\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/polar_express/reviews?type=top_critics&sort=&page=3|title=The Polar Express - Movie Reviews|accessdate=January 7, 2020|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref> and \"an enchanting, beautiful and brilliantly imagined film that constitutes a technological breakthrough.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/High-tech-magic-and-true-feeling-make-Express-a-2637142.php|title=High-tech magic and true feeling make 'Express' a holiday classic|accessdate=January 7, 2020|website=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]}}</ref> [[James Berardinelli]] gave the film 3.5 out of 4 stars, stating that it is \"a delightful tale guaranteed to enthrall viewers of all ages\", and ranked it as the 10th best film of 2004, tying with ''[[The Incredibles]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/polar-express-the|title=Polar Express, The (United States, 2004)|last=Berardinelli|first=James|work=ReelViews.net|accessdate=2017-10-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907060435/http://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/polar-express-the|archive-date=September 7, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Ian Nathan of ''[[Empire Magazine]]'' gave the film three out of five stars, and said: \"For all the fairy-lit wonder, some will rail at the idea of ''[[Back to the Future]]''{{'}}s director dabbling with such a schmaltzy tale. Cynics will sneeze in shock; children will cuddle up and dream along.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Polar Express, The Review|url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/reviews/polar-express-review/|accessdate=January 7, 2020|website=[[Empire Magazine]]}}</ref> [[Peter Bradshaw]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' also gave the film three out of five stars, saying: \"After a promising and distinctive start, a railway adventure to meet Santa runs off the rails.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The Polar Express review \u2013 a trainful of sugar|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/04/polar-express-review-3d-robert-zemeckis|accessdate=January 7, 2020|website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nThe character design and animation were criticized for dipping into the [[uncanny valley]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/express/wp/2015/05/07/the-d-train-isnt-actually-about-trains-but-these-5-movies-are/|title='The D Train' isn't actually about trains. But these 5 movies are.|last=Page-Kirby|first=Kristen|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2015-05-07|accessdate=2015-06-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022032816/https://www.washingtonpost.com/express/wp/2015/05/07/the-d-train-isnt-actually-about-trains-but-these-5-movies-are/|archive-date=October 22, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' gave the film one out of four stars, and called it \"a failed and lifeless experiment in which everything goes wrong\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/the-polar-express-20041118|title=The Polar Express|last=Travers|first=Peter|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=2004-11-18|accessdate=2015-06-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022084921/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/the-polar-express-20041118|archive-date=October 22, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Stephanie Zacharek of ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'' gave the film 1.5 stars out of 5 and said: \"I could probably have tolerated the incessant jitteriness of ''The Polar Express'' if the look of it didn't give me the creeps.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/2004/11/10/polar_express/|title=The Polar Express|last=Zacharek|first=Stephanie|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|date=2004-11-10|accessdate=2015-06-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623212933/http://www.salon.com/2004/11/10/polar_express/|archive-date=June 23, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Geoff Pevere]] of the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' stated: \"If I were a child, I'd have nightmares. Come to think of it, I did anyway.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/2013/11/01/10-scariest-movies-and-why-they-creep-us-out-243852.html|title=The 10 Scariest Movies and Why They Creep Us Out|last=Herman|first=Barbara|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=2013-10-30|accessdate=2015-06-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623214401/http://www.newsweek.com/2013/11/01/10-scariest-movies-and-why-they-creep-us-out-243852.html|archive-date=June 23, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Paul Clinton]] from [[CNN]] called it \"at best disconcerting, and at worst, a wee bit horrifying\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2004/SHOWBIZ/Movies/11/10/review.polar.express/index.html|title=Review: 'Polar Express' a creepy ride|last=Clinton|first=Paul|work=[[CNN]]|date=2004-11-10|accessdate=2015-06-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150527212747/http://www.cnn.com/2004/SHOWBIZ/Movies/11/10/review.polar.express/index.html|archive-date=May 27, 2015|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><!--[[Manohla Dargis]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote: \"There's no way of knowing whether they drank the company Kool-Aid. Still, from the looks of ''The Polar Express'' it's clear that, together with Mr. Zemeckis, this talented gang has on some fundamental level lost touch with the human aspect of film.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Do You Hear Sleigh Bells? Nah, Just Tom Hanks and Some Train|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/11/10/movies/do-you-hear-sleigh-bells-nah-just-tom-hanks-and-some-train.html|accessdate=January 7, 2020|website=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>-->\n\n===Accolades===\n{{expand section|date=January 2020}}\nIn 2008, the [[American Film Institute]] nominated ''The Polar Express'' for its [[AFI's 10 Top 10#Animation|Top 10 Animated Films list]].<ref>{{cite web|title=AFI'S 10 Top 10 - Official Ballot|url=http://connect.afi.com/site/DocServer/10top10.pdf?docID=381&AddInterest=1781|publisher=AFI|accessdate=September 8, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716071937/http://connect.afi.com/site/DocServer/10top10.pdf?docID=381&AddInterest=1781|archivedate=July 16, 2011|date=2008}}</ref> The film was nominated at the [[77th Academy Awards]]in the categories of [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Best Sound Editing]] ([[Randy Thom]] and [[Dennis Leonard (sound editor)|Dennis Leonard]]), [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound Mixing]] (Randy Thom, [[Tom Johnson (sound engineer)|Tom Johnson]], [[Dennis S. Sands]] and [[William B. Kaplan]]) and [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for \"[[Believe (Josh Groban song)|Believe]]\" (music and lyrics by [[Glen Ballard]] and [[Alan Silvestri]]).<ref name=\"Oscars2005\">{{cite web|title=Academy Awards Database: 2004 (77th)|url=http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1415761726141|accessdate=2014-11-12|publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]}}{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref> The film was nominated at the [[3rd Visual Effects Society Awards]] in the category of \"Outstanding Performance by an Animated Character in an Animated Motion Picture.\"<ref name=\"VisualAwards2005\">{{cite web|url=https://www.visualeffectssociety.com/ayear/3rd-annual-ves-awards|title=3rd Annual VES Awards|work=Visual Effects Society|accessdate=December 19, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308071358/https://www.visualeffectssociety.com/ayear/3rd-annual-ves-awards|archive-date=March 8, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Date of ceremony\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Academy Awards]]\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[77th Academy Awards|February 27, 2005]]\n| [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Best Sound Editing]]\n| [[Randy Thom]] and [[Dennis Leonard (sound editor)|Dennis Leonard]]\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\"| <ref name=\"Oscars2005\"/>\n|-\n| [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound Mixing]]\n| Randy Thom, [[Tom Johnson (sound engineer)|Tom Johnson]], [[Dennis S. Sands]] and [[William B. Kaplan]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]]\n| [[Glen Ballard]] and [[Alan Silvestri]] for \"[[Believe (The Polar Express song)|Believe]]\" by [[Josh Groban]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Globe Awards]]\n| [[62nd Golden Globe Awards|January 16, 2005]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]]\n| Glen Ballard and Alan Silvestri for \"Believe\" by Josh Groban\n| {{nom}}\n| \n|-\n| [[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]]\n| [[48th Annual Grammy Awards|February 8, 2006]]\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media|Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media]]\n| Glen Ballard and Alan Silvestri for \"Believe\" by Josh Groban\n| {{won}}\n| \n|-\n| [[Visual Effects Society]]\n| [[3rd Visual Effects Society Awards|February 16, 2005]]\n| [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Outstanding Performance by an Animated Character in an Animated Motion Pictureg]]\n| [[Michael Jeter]], [[David Schaub]], Renato Dos Anjos, Roger Vizard for Steamer\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref name=\"VisualAwards2005\"/>\n|}\n\n==Train trips==\n[[File:Polar_Express_train_at_Dereham.jpg|thumb|right|Polar Express train on the [[Mid-Norfolk Railway]] in 2019.]]\nThe film has also spawned multiple real-world holiday train-travel experiences based loosely on the film's train journey all over America and the United Kingdom under licence from Rail Events Inc.<ref>{{cite web|title=THE POLAR EXPRESS\u2122 Train Ride|url=https://www.raileventsinc.com/polar-express|accessdate=January 7, 2020|publisher=Rail Events Inc.}}</ref>\n \nThese include the Polar Express train ride held at the Grand Canyon Railway and Hotel,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetrain.com/events/polar-express/ | title = All Aboard to the North Pole | publisher= Grand Canyon Railway & Hotel | accessdate =February 4, 2019}}</ref> and the Polar Express Train Ride of the Great Smoky Mountains Railroad,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gsmr.com/events/polar-express#.XFi6c_ZFyUk | title=The Polar Express Train Ride |publisher=Great Smokey Mountains Railroad|accessdate=February 4, 2019}}</ref> The Polar Express Train Ride at Aspen Crossing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aspencrossing.com/polar-express | title=The Polar Express Train Ride |publisher=Aspen Crossing|accessdate=October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe UK's first Polar Express train rides were hosted on the [[Dartmoor Railway]] and the [[Weardale Railway]] which were both owned by the company [[British American Railway Services]]. These services were all diesel hauled, however in 2016, [[Telford Steam Railway]] became the first UK line to run the Polar Express with steam which ended in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=THE POLAR EXPRESS\u2122 Train Ride 2016|url=https://telfordsteamrailway.co.uk/event/the-polar-express-train-ride/|accessdate=January 7, 2020|publisher=Telford Steam Railway}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=THE POLAR EXPRESS\u2122 Train Ride 2017|url=https://telfordsteamrailway.co.uk/event/polar-express-train-ride-2017/|accessdate=January 7, 2020|publisher=Telford Steam Railway}}</ref>\n\n==The ''Polar Express'' Experience==\nIn November 2007, [[SeaWorld Orlando]] debuted the ''Polar Express'' Experience, a [[motion simulator]] ride based on the film. The attraction was a temporary replacement for the [[Wild Arctic]] attraction. The building housing the attraction was also temporarily re-themed to a railroad station and ride vehicles painted to resemble Polar Express passenger cars. The plot for the ride revolves around a trip to the North Pole on Christmas Eve. Guests feel the motion of the locomotive as well as the swinging of the train on ice and feeling of ice crumbling beneath them. The attraction was available until January 1, 2008,<ref name=SeaWorld>{{cite web| title=The Polar Express Experience at SeaWorld Orlando Begins This Friday, November 12th...| date=November 10, 2010| publisher=Visit Tampa Bay| url=http://www.visittampabay.com/blog/bay-blogger/the-polar-express-experience-at-seaworld-orlando-begins-this-friday-november-12th| accessdate=2014-11-12| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112194738/http://www.visittampabay.com/blog/bay-blogger/the-polar-express-experience-at-seaworld-orlando-begins-this-friday-november-12th| archivedate=November 12, 2014| df=mdy-all}}</ref> and was open annually during the Christmas season. 2015 was the final year of operation for the ''Polar Express'' Experience and Wild Arctic has since operated on a year-round schedule.\n\nThe [[4D film]], distributed by [[SimEx-Iwerks]], has been shown at other amusement parks around the world including [[Cincinnati Zoo and Botanical Garden]], [[Dollywood]] (during the annual Smoky Mountain Christmas event), [[Vancouver Aquarium]] (2009\u20142010),<ref>{{cite news| title=Polar Express 4-D Experience| date=November 30, 2009| url=http://www.visitvanaqua.org/news/4D| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090707084328/http://www.visitvanaqua.org/news/4D| url-status=dead| archive-date=July 7, 2009}}</ref> and [[Warner Bros. Movie World]] (during the [[White Christmas (Warner Bros. Movie World)|White Christmas events]] in 2010 and 2011).\n\n==Video game==\n{{Main|The Polar Express (video game)}}\nA video game based on the film was released on November 26, 2004 for [[GameCube]], [[Game Boy Advance]], [[PlayStation 2]] and [[Windows]], developed by [[Blue Tongue Entertainment]] and published by [[THQ]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Adams |first=David |date=May 4, 2004 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2004/05/04/pre-e3-2004-thq-announces-lineup |title=Pre-E3 2004: THQ Announces Lineup |journal=[[IGN]] |accessdate=December 24, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224020353/http://www.ign.com/articles/2004/05/04/pre-e3-2004-thq-announces-lineup |archive-date=December 24, 2014 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.playstation.com/games-media/games/detail/item35910/Polar-Express |title=PlayStation Games & Media - Polar Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224050426/http://uk.playstation.com/ps2/games/detail/item35910/Polar-Express/ |archive-date=December 24, 2014 |work=[[PlayStation]] |access-date=January 4, 2018 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The plot of the game is somewhat different than the film version. Within the game, the Ebenezer Scrooge puppet\u2014who is set as the main antagonist of the game\u2014attempts to prevent the children from believing in Santa Claus by stealing their tickets and trying to stop the children from making it to the North Pole.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Casamassina |first=Matt |date=November 8, 2004 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2004/11/09/the-polar-express-4 |title=The Polar Express (GCN, PS2) |journal=[[IGN]] |accessdate=December 24, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224012351/http://www.ign.com/articles/2004/11/09/the-polar-express-4 |archive-date=December 24, 2014 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Gerstmann |first=Jeff |date=May 12, 2004 |url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-polar-express-e3-2004-preshow-first-look/1100-6096607/ |title=The Polar Express E3 2004 Preshow First Look |journal=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=December 24, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313083128/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-polar-express-e3-2004-preshow-first-look/1100-6096607/ |archive-date=March 13, 2014 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of 3D films (2005 onwards)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book|last1=Cotta Vaz|first1=Mark|last2=Starky|first2=Steve|year=2004|title=The Art of the Polar Express|edition=1st|publisher=[[Chronicle Books]]|isbn=978-0811846592|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|The Polar Express}}\n* {{Official website|http://pdl.warnerbros.com/wbmovies/polarexpress/flashsite/}}\n* {{IMDb title|0338348}}\n* {{tcmdb title|452714}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|polar_express}}\n* {{Mojo title|polarexpress}}\n\n{{Robert Zemeckis}}\n{{Chris Van Allsburg}}\n{{Warner Bros. theatrical animated features}}\n{{Warner Christmas films}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Polar Express, The}}\n[[Category:2004 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2004 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:2000s 3D films]]\n[[Category:3D animated films]]\n[[Category:2000s American animated films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:2000s fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:2000s Christmas films]]\n[[Category:2000s children's animated films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:American Christmas films]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy films]]\n[[Category:Animated Christmas films]]\n[[Category:Animated films about trains]]\n[[Category:Animated films based on children's books]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Chris Van Allsburg]]\n[[Category:Christmas adventure films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Films set in Canada]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Arctic]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1950s]]\n[[Category:Films set on trains]]\n[[Category:Fictional trains]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:Motion capture in film]]\n[[Category:Santa Claus in film]]\n[[Category:Rail transport films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Robert Zemeckis]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Gary Goetzman]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Robert Zemeckis]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Alan Silvestri]]\n[[Category:Films about elves]]\n[[Category:ImageMovers films]]\n[[Category:Playtone films]]\n[[Category:Shangri-La Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Castle Rock Entertainment films]]\n